# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hydrogen
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hydrogen/1000000000-number] In standard form, it is written as **1 × 109**.
[src:hydrogen/1000000000-number] The metric prefix giga indicates 1,000,000,000 times the base unit.
[src:hydrogen/1000000000-number] One billion years may be called an *eon* in astronomy or geology.
[src:hydrogen/1000000000-number] Previously in British English (but not in American English), the word "billion" referred exclusively to a million millions (1,000,000,000,000).
[src:hydrogen/1000000000-number] However, this is not common anymore, and the word has been used to mean one thousand million (1,000,000,000) for several decades.
[src:hydrogen/1000000000-number] The term ***milliard*** could also be used to refer to 1,000,000,000; whereas "milliard" is rarely used in English, variations on this name often appear in other languages.
[src:hydrogen/1000000000-number] In the Indian numbering system, it is known as 100 crore or 1 arab.
[src:hydrogen/1000000000-number] It is a common metric used in macroeconomics when describing national economies.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] On May 28, 2002 (sol 210), NASA reported that *Odyssey*'s GRS instrument had detected large amounts of hydrogen, a sign that there must be ice lying within a meter of the planet's surface, and proceeded to map the distribution of water below the shallow surface.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] The orbiter also discovered vast deposits of bulk water ice near the surface of equatorial regions.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] In August 2000, NASA solicited candidate names for the mission.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] Out of 200 names submitted, the committee chose Astrobiological Reconnaissance and Elemental Surveyor, abbreviated ARES (a tribute to Ares, the Greek god of war).
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] Faced with criticism that this name was not very compelling, and too aggressive, the naming committee reconvened.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] The candidate name "2001 Mars Odyssey" had earlier been rejected because of copyright and trademark concerns.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] Clarke in Sri Lanka, who responded that he would be delighted to have the mission named after his books, and he had no objections.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] On September 20, NASA associate administrator Ed Weiler wrote to the associate administrator for public affairs recommending a name change from ARES to *2001 Mars Odyssey*.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] Peggy Wilhide then approved the name change.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] Aerobraking ended in January 2002, and Odyssey began its science mapping mission on February 19, 2002.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] *Odyssey*'s original, nominal mission lasted until August 2004, but repeated mission extensions have kept the mission active.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] The payload's MARIE radiation experiment stopped taking measurements after a large solar event bombarded the *Odyssey* spacecraft on October 28, 2003.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] Engineers believe the most likely cause is that a computer chip was damaged by a solar particle smashing into the MARIE computer board.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] About 85% of images and other data from NASA's twin Mars Exploration Rovers, *Spirit* and *Opportunity*, have reached Earth via communications relay by *Odyssey*.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] The orbiter helped analyze potential landing sites for the rovers and performed the same task for NASA's Phoenix mission, which landed on Mars in May 2008.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] *Odyssey* aided NASA's *Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter*, which reached Mars in March 2006, by monitoring atmospheric conditions during months when the newly arrived orbiter used aerobraking to alter its orbit into the desired shape.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] By December 15, 2010, it broke the record for longest serving spacecraft at Mars, with 3,340 days of operation.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] The orbiter's orientation is controlled by a set of three reaction wheels and a spare.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] When one failed in June 2012, the fourth was spun up and successfully brought into service.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] Since July 2012, *Odyssey* has been back in full, nominal operation mode following three weeks of 'safe' mode on remote maintenance.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] On February 11, 2014, mission control accelerated *Odyssey*'s drift toward a morning-daylight orbit to "enable observation of changing ground temperatures after sunrise and after sunset in thousands of places on Mars".
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] The orbital change occurred gradually until November 2015.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] Those observations could yield insight about the composition of the ground and about temperature-driven processes, such as warm seasonal flows observed on some slopes, and geysers fed by spring thawing of carbon dioxide (CO2) ice near Mars's poles.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] On October 19, 2014, NASA reported that the *Mars Odyssey* Orbiter, as well as the *Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter* and *MAVEN*, were healthy after the Comet Siding Spring flyby.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] In 2010, a spokesman for NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory stated that *Odyssey* could continue operating until at least 2016.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] This estimate has since been extended to the end of 2025.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] By 2008, *Mars Odyssey* had mapped the basic distribution of water below the shallow surface.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] The ground truth for its measurements came on July 31, 2008, when NASA announced that the Phoenix lander confirmed the presence of water on Mars, as predicted in 2002 based on data from the *Odyssey* orbiter.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] The science team is trying to determine whether the water ice ever thaws enough to be available for microscopic life, and if carbon-containing chemicals and other raw materials for life are present.
[src:hydrogen/2001-mars-odyssey] Evidence for equatorial hydration is both morphological and compositional and is seen at both the Medusae Fossae formation and the Tharsis Montes.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The **abundance of the chemical elements** is a measure of the occurrences of the chemical elements relative to all other elements in a given environment.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Abundance is measured in one of three ways: by *mass fraction* (in commercial contexts often called *weight fraction*), by *mole fraction* (fraction of atoms by numerical count, or sometimes fraction of molecules in gases), or by *volume fraction*.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Volume fraction is a common abundance measure in mixed gases such as planetary atmospheres, and is similar in value to molecular mole fraction for gas mixtures at relatively low densities and pressures, and ideal gas mixtures.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Most abundance values in this article are given as mass fractions.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The abundance of chemical elements in the universe is dominated by the large amounts of hydrogen and helium which were produced during Big Bang nucleosynthesis.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Remaining elements, making up only about 2% of the universe, were largely produced by supernova nucleosynthesis.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Elements with even atomic numbers are generally more common than their neighbors in the periodic table, due to their favorable energetics of formation, described by the Oddo–Harkins rule.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The abundance of elements in the Sun and outer planets is similar to that in the universe.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Due to solar heating, the elements of Earth and the inner rocky planets of the Solar System have undergone an additional depletion of volatile hydrogen, helium, neon, nitrogen, and carbon (which volatilizes as methane).
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The crust, mantle, and core of the Earth show evidence of chemical segregation plus some sequestration by density.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Lighter silicates of aluminium are found in the crust, with more magnesium silicate in the mantle, while metallic iron and nickel compose the core.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The abundance of elements in specialized environments, such as atmospheres, oceans, or the human body, are primarily a product of chemical interactions with the medium in which they reside.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Abundance of each element is expressed as a relative number.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Astronomy uses a logarithmic scale for abundance $\epsilon _{X}$ of element X relative to hydrogen, defined by $\epsilon _{X}\equiv \log(N_{X}/N_{H})+12.00$ for number density N ; $\epsilon _{H}=12.00$ on this scale.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Another scale is mass fraction or, equivalently, percent by mass.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] For example, the abundance of oxygen in pure water can be measured in two ways: the *mass fraction* is about 89%, because that is the fraction of water's mass which is oxygen.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] However, the *mole fraction* is about 33% because only 1 atom of 3 in water, H2O, is oxygen.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Changing the given environment to Jupiter's outer atmosphere, where hydrogen is diatomic while helium is not, changes the *molecular* mole fraction (fraction of total gas molecules), as well as the fraction of atmosphere by volume, of hydrogen to about 86%, and of helium to 13%.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Below Jupiter's outer atmosphere, volume fractions are significantly different from mole fractions due to high temperatures (ionization and disproportionation) and high density, where the ideal gas law is inapplicable.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Remaining elements, making up only about 2% of the universe, were largely produced by supernovae and certain red giant stars.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Lithium, beryllium, and boron, despite their low atomic number, are rare because, although they are produced by nuclear fusion, they are destroyed by other reactions in the stars.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Their natural occurrence is the result of cosmic ray spallation of carbon, nitrogen and oxygen in a type of nuclear fission reaction.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The elements from carbon to iron are relatively more abundant in the universe because of the ease of making them in supernova nucleosynthesis.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Elements of higher atomic numbers than iron (element 26) become progressively rarer in the universe, because they increasingly absorb stellar energy in their production.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Also, elements with even atomic numbers are generally more common than their neighbors in the periodic table, due to favorable energetics of formation (see Oddo–Harkins rule), and among the lightest nuclides helium through sulfur the most abundant isotopes of equal number of protons and neutrons.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Hydrogen is the most abundant element in the Universe; helium is second.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] All others are orders of magnitude less common.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] After this, the rank of abundance does not continue to correspond to the atomic number.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Oxygen has abundance rank 3, but atomic number 8.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] There are 80 known stable elements, and the lightest 16 comprise 99.9% of the ordinary matter of the universe.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The Segrè plot is initially linear because (aside from hydrogen) the vast majority of ordinary matter (99.4% in the Solar System) contains an equal number of protons and neutrons (Z=N).
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The abundance of the elements up to lithium is well predicted by the standard cosmological model, since they were mostly produced shortly (i.e., within a few hundred seconds) after the Big Bang, in a process known as Big Bang nucleosynthesis.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Heavier elements were mostly produced much later, in stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] In general, elements up to iron are made by large stars in the process of becoming supernovae, or by smaller stars in the process of dying.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Iron-56 is particularly common, since it is the most stable nuclide (in that it has the highest nuclear binding energy per nucleon) and can easily be "built up" from alpha particles (being a product of decay of radioactive nickel-56, ultimately made from 14 helium nuclei).
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Elements heavier than iron are made in energy-absorbing processes in large stars, and their abundance in the universe (and on Earth) generally decreases with increasing atomic number.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The table shows the ten most common elements in our galaxy (estimated spectroscopically), as measured in parts per million, by mass.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Nearby galaxies that have evolved along similar lines have a corresponding enrichment of elements heavier than hydrogen and helium.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The more distant galaxies are being viewed as they appeared in the past, so their abundances of elements appear closer to the primordial mixture.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Since physical laws and processes are apparently uniform throughout the universe, however, it is expected that these galaxies will likewise have evolved similar abundances of elements.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] As shown in the periodic table, the abundance of elements is in keeping with their origin.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Very abundant hydrogen and helium are products of the Big Bang.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The next three elements in the periodic table (lithium, beryllium, and boron) are rare, despite their low atomic number.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] They had little time to form in the Big Bang.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] They are produced in small quantities by nuclear fusion in dying stars or by breakup of heavier elements in interstellar dust, caused by cosmic ray spallation.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] In supernova stars, they are produced by nuclear fusion, but then destroyed by other reactions.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Heavier elements, beginning with carbon, have been produced in dying or supernova stars by buildup from alpha particles (helium nuclei), contributing to an alternatingly larger abundance of elements with even atomic numbers (these are also more stable).
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The effect of odd-numbered chemical elements generally being more rare in the universe was empirically noticed in 1914, and is known as the Oddo–Harkins rule.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The following graph (log scale) shows abundance of elements in the Solar System.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Loose correlations have been observed between estimated elemental abundances in the universe and the nuclear binding energy curve (also called the *binding energy per nucleon*).
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Roughly speaking, the relative stability of various atomic nuclides in withstanding the extremely energetic conditions of Big Bang nucleosynthesis (BBN) has exerted a strong influence on the relative abundance of elements formed in the Big Bang, and during the development of the universe thereafter.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] See the article about nucleosynthesis for an explanation of how certain nuclear fusion processes in stars (such as carbon burning, etc.) create the elements heavier than hydrogen and helium.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] A similar alternation between even and odd atomic numbers can be observed in the nuclear binding energy curve in the neighborhood of carbon and oxygen, but here the loose correlation between relative abundance and binding energy ends.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The binding energy for beryllium (an even atomic number), for example, is *less* than the binding energy for boron (an odd atomic number), as illustrated in the nuclear binding energy curve.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Additionally, the alternation in the nuclear binding energy between even and odd atomic numbers resolves above oxygen as the graph increases steadily up to its peak at iron.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The semi-empirical mass formula (SEMF), also called *Weizsäcker's formula* or the *Bethe-Weizsäcker mass formula*, gives a theoretical explanation of the overall shape of the curve of nuclear binding energy.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Modern astronomy relies on understanding the abundance of elements in the Sun as part of cosmological models.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Abundance values are difficult to obtain: even photospheric or observational abundances depend upon models of solar atmospherics and radiation coupling.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] These astronomical abundance values are reported as logarithms of the ratio with hydrogen.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Hydrogen is set to an abundance of 12 on this scale.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The Sun's photosphere consists mostly of hydrogen and helium; the helium abundance varies between about 10.3 and 10.5 depending on the phase of the solar cycle; carbon is 8.47, neon is 8.29, oxygen is 7.69 and iron is estimated at 7.62.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The Earth formed from the same cloud of matter that formed the Sun, but the planets acquired different compositions during the formation and evolution of the Solar System.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] In turn, the history of Earth led to parts of the planet having differing concentrations of the elements.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The mass of the Earth is approximately 5.97×1024 kg.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] By mass, it is composed mostly of iron (32.1%), oxygen (30.1%), silicon (15.1%), magnesium (13.9%), sulfur (2.9%), nickel (1.8%), calcium (1.5%), and aluminium (1.4%); with the remaining 1.2% consisting of trace amounts of other elements.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The amount of oxygen, silicon, sulfur, carbon, and hydrogen in the Earth's core can only be inferred from theoretical models and consequently the abundance of these elements in the total Earth is not known precisely.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The remaining elemental composition is roughly typical of the "rocky" inner planets, which formed "inside" the "frost line" close to the Sun, where the young Sun's heat and stellar wind drove off volatile compounds into space.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The Earth retains oxygen as the second-largest component of its mass (and largest atomic fraction), mainly due to oxygen's high reactivity; this caused it to bond into silicate minerals which have a high melting point and low vapor pressure.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The mass-abundance of the nine most abundant elements in the Earth's crust is roughly: oxygen 46%, silicon 28%, aluminium 8.3%, iron 5.6%, calcium 4.2%, sodium 2.5%, magnesium 2.4%, potassium 2.0%, and titanium 0.61%.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Other elements occur at less than 0.15%.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] For a full list, see abundance of elements in Earth's crust.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The graph at right illustrates the relative atomic-abundance of the chemical elements in Earth's upper continental crust—the part that is relatively accessible for measurements and estimation.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] 5. the nine rarest "metals" – the six platinum group elements plus Au, Re, and Te (a metalloid) – in the yellow field.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] These are rare in the crust from being soluble in iron and thus concentrated in Earth's core.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Tellurium is the single most depleted element in the silicate Earth relative to cosmic abundance, because in addition to being concentrated as dense chalcogenides in the core it was severely depleted by preaccretional sorting in the nebula as volatile hydrogen telluride.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] There are two breaks where the unstable elements technetium (atomic number 43) and promethium (number 61) would be.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] These elements are surrounded by stable elements, yet their most stable isotopes have relatively short half-lives (~4 million years and ~18 years respectively).
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] These are thus extremely rare, since any primordial amounts of these elements have long since decayed.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] These two elements are now only produced naturally through spontaneous fission of very heavy radioactive elements (such as uranium, thorium, or the trace amounts of plutonium that exist in uranium ores), or by the interaction of certain other elements with cosmic rays.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Both technetium and promethium have been identified spectroscopically in the atmospheres of stars, where they are produced by ongoing nucleosynthetic processes.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] There are also breaks in the abundance graph where the six noble gases would be, since they are not chemically bound in the Earth's crust, and so their crustal abundance is not well-defined.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Oxygen and silicon are the most common elements in the crust.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] On Earth and rocky planets in general, silicon and oxygen are far more common than their cosmic abundance.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The reason is that they combine with each other to form silicate minerals.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Other cosmically common elements such as hydrogen, carbon and nitrogen form volatile compounds such as ammonia and methane that easily boil away into space from the heat of planetary formation and/or the Sun's light.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] "Rare" earth elements is a historical misnomer.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The persistence of the term reflects unfamiliarity rather than true rarity.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The more abundant rare earth elements are similarly concentrated in the crust compared to commonplace industrial metals such as chromium, nickel, copper, zinc, molybdenum, tin, tungsten, or lead.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The two least abundant stable rare earth elements (thulium and lutetium) are nearly 200 times more common than gold.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] However, in contrast to the ordinary base and precious metals, rare earth elements have very little tendency to become concentrated in exploitable ore deposits.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Consequently, most of the world's supply of rare earth elements comes from only a handful of sources.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Furthermore, the rare earth metals are all quite chemically similar to each other, and they are thus quite difficult to separate into quantities of the pure elements.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Differences in abundances of individual rare earth elements in the upper continental crust of the Earth represent the superposition of two effects, one nuclear and one geochemical.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] First, the rare earth elements with even atomic numbers (58Ce, 60Nd, ...) have greater cosmic and terrestrial abundances than the adjacent rare earth elements with odd atomic numbers (57La, 59Pr, ...).
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Second, the lighter rare earth elements are more incompatible (because they have larger ionic radii) and therefore more strongly concentrated in the continental crust than the heavier rare earth elements.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] In most rare earth ore deposits, the first four rare earth elements – lanthanum, cerium, praseodymium, and neodymium – constitute 80% to 99% of the total amount of rare earth metal that can be found in the ore.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The mass-abundance of the seven most abundant elements in the Earth's mantle is approximately: oxygen 44.3%, magnesium 22.3%, silicon 21.3%, iron 6.32%, calcium 2.48%, aluminium 2.29%, nickel 0.19%.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Due to mass segregation, the core of the Earth is believed to be primarily composed of iron (88.8%), with smaller amounts of nickel (5.8%), sulfur (4.5%), and less than 1% trace elements.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Sulfur, phosphorus, and all other elements are present in significantly lower proportions.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] According to the abundance curve graph, argon, a significant if not major component of the atmosphere, does not appear in the crust at all.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] This is because the atmosphere has a far smaller mass than the crust, so argon remaining in the crust contributes little to mass fraction there, while at the same time buildup of argon in the atmosphere has become large enough to be significant.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] By mass, human cells consist of 65–90% water (H2O), and a significant portion of the remainder is composed of carbon-containing organic molecules.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Oxygen therefore contributes a majority of a human body's mass, followed by carbon.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Almost 99% of the mass of the human body is made up of six elements: hydrogen (H), carbon (C), nitrogen (N), oxygen (O), calcium (Ca), and phosphorus (P).
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The next 0.75% is made up of the next five elements: potassium (K), sulfur (S), chlorine (Cl), sodium (Na), and magnesium (Mg).
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Only 17 elements are known for certain to be necessary to human life, with one additional element (fluorine) thought to be helpful for tooth enamel strength.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] A few more trace elements may play some role in the health of mammals.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Boron and silicon are notably necessary for plants but have uncertain roles in animals.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The elements aluminium and silicon, although very common in the earth's crust, are conspicuously rare in the human body.
[src:hydrogen/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Below is a periodic table highlighting nutritional elements.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] In chemistry, an **acid–base reaction** is a chemical reaction that occurs between an acid and a base.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] It can be used to determine pH via titration.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Several theoretical frameworks provide alternative conceptions of the reaction mechanisms and their application in solving related problems; these are called the acid–base theories, for example, Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Their importance becomes apparent in analyzing acid–base reactions for gaseous or liquid species, or when acid or base character may be somewhat less apparent.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The first of these concepts was provided by the French chemist Antoine Lavoisier, around 1776.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] It is important to think of the acid–base reaction models as theories that complement each other.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] For example, the current Lewis model has the broadest definition of what an acid and base are, with the Brønsted–Lowry theory being a subset of what acids and bases are, and the Arrhenius theory being the most restrictive.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The Arrhenius theory describes an acid as a substance that increases the concentration of hydrogen ions (H3O+ or H+) in a solution.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] A base is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide ions (OH-) in a solution.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] However, Arrhenius's definition only applies to substances that are in water.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The concept of an acid–base reaction was first proposed in 1754 by Guillaume-François Rouelle, who introduced the word "base" into chemistry to mean a substance which reacts with an acid to give it solid form (as a salt).
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The first scientific concept of acids and bases was provided by Lavoisier in around 1776.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The Lavoisier definition held for over 30 years, until the 1810 article and subsequent lectures by Sir Humphry Davy in which he proved the lack of oxygen in hydrogen sulfide (H2S), hydrogen telluride (H2Te), and the hydrohalic acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] However, Davy failed to develop a new theory, concluding that "acidity does not depend upon any particular elementary substance, but upon peculiar arrangement of various substances".
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] One notable modification of oxygen theory was provided by Jöns Jacob Berzelius, who stated that acids are oxides of nonmetals while bases are oxides of metals.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] In 1838, Justus von Liebig proposed that an acid is a hydrogen-containing compound whose hydrogen can be replaced by a metal.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] This redefinition was based on his extensive work on the chemical composition of organic acids, finishing the doctrinal shift from oxygen-based acids to hydrogen-based acids started by Davy.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Liebig's definition, while completely empirical, remained in use for almost 50 years until the adoption of the Arrhenius definition.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The first modern definition of acids and bases in molecular terms was devised by Svante Arrhenius.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] A hydrogen theory of acids, it followed from his 1884 work with Friedrich Wilhelm Ostwald in establishing the presence of ions in aqueous solution and led to Arrhenius receiving the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1903.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] This causes the protonation of water, or the creation of the hydronium (H3O+) ion.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Thus, in modern times, the symbol H+ is interpreted as a shorthand for H3O+, because it is now known that a bare proton does not exist as a free species in aqueous solution.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] This is the species which is measured by pH indicators to measure the acidity or basicity of a solution.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The Arrhenius definitions of acidity and alkalinity are restricted to aqueous solutions and are not valid for most non-aqueous solutions, and refer to the concentration of the solvent ions.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Under this definition, pure H2SO4 and HCl dissolved in toluene are not acidic, and molten NaOH and solutions of calcium amide in liquid ammonia are not alkaline.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] This led to the development of the Brønsted–Lowry theory and subsequent Lewis theory to account for these non-aqueous exceptions.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The reaction of an acid with a base is called a neutralization reaction.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] In this traditional representation an acid–base neutralization reaction is formulated as a double-replacement reaction.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The modifier (aq) in this equation was implied by Arrhenius, rather than included explicitly.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] It indicates that the substances are dissolved in water.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Though all three substances, HCl, NaOH and NaCl are capable of existing as pure compounds, in aqueous solutions they are fully dissociated into the aquated ions H+, Cl−, Na+ and OH−.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Baking powder is used to cause the dough for breads and cakes to "rise" by creating millions of tiny carbon dioxide bubbles.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Baking powder is not to be confused with baking soda, which is sodium bicarbonate (NaHCO3).
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Baking powder is a mixture of baking soda (sodium bicarbonate) and acidic salts.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The bubbles are created because, when the baking powder is combined with water, the sodium bicarbonate and acid salts react to produce gaseous carbon dioxide.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Whether commercially or domestically prepared, the principles behind baking powder formulations remain the same.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The real reactions are more complicated because the acids are complicated.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] A typical formulation (by weight) could call for 30% sodium bicarbonate, 5–12% monocalcium phosphate, and 21–26% sodium aluminium sulfate.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Alternately, a commercial baking powder might use sodium acid pyrophosphate as one of the two acidic components instead of sodium aluminium sulfate.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Another typical acid in such formulations is cream of tartar (KC4H5O6), a derivative of tartaric acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] An acid–base reaction is, thus, the removal of a proton from the acid and its addition to the base.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The removal of a proton from an acid produces its *conjugate base*, which is the acid with a proton removed.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The reception of a proton by a base produces its *conjugate acid*, which is the base with a proton added.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Unlike the previous definitions, the Brønsted–Lowry definition does not refer to the formation of salt and solvent, but instead to the formation of *conjugate acids* and *conjugate bases*, produced by the transfer of a proton from the acid to the base.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] In this approach, acids and bases are fundamentally different in behavior from salts, which are seen as electrolytes, subject to the theories of Debye, Onsager, and others.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] An acid and a base react not to produce a salt and a solvent, but to form a new acid and a new base.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The concept of neutralization is thus absent.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base behavior is formally independent of any solvent, making it more all-encompassing than the Arrhenius model.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The calculation of pH under the Arrhenius model depended on alkalis (bases) dissolving in water (aqueous solution).
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The Brønsted–Lowry model expanded what could be pH tested using insoluble and soluble solutions (gas, liquid, solid).
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The general formula for acid–base reactions according to the Brønsted–Lowry definition is: ${\ce {HA + B -> BH+ + A-}}$ where HA represents the acid, B represents the base, BH+ represents the conjugate acid of B, and A− represents the conjugate base of HA.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The removal of H+ from the HCl produces the chloride ion, Cl−, the conjugate base of the acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The addition of H+ to the H2O (acting as a base) forms the hydronium ion, H3O+, the conjugate acid of the base.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Water is amphoteric – that is, it can act as both an acid and a base.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Here, one molecule of water acts as an acid, donating an H+ and forming the conjugate base, OH−, and a second molecule of water acts as a base, accepting the H+ ion and forming the conjugate acid, H3O+.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] In this example, a water molecule is split into a hydrogen cation, which is donated to a pyridine molecule, and a hydroxide ion.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] In the Brønsted–Lowry model, the solvent does not necessarily have to be water, as is required by the Arrhenius Acid–Base model.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] An H+ ion is removed from acetic acid, forming its conjugate base, the acetate ion, CH3COO−.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The addition of an H+ ion to an ammonia molecule of the solvent creates its conjugate acid, the ammonium ion, NH+4.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The Brønsted–Lowry model calls hydrogen-containing substances (like HCl) acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Thus, some substances, which many chemists considered to be acids, such as SO3 or BCl3, are excluded from this classification due to lack of hydrogen.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The hydrogen requirement of Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry was removed by the Lewis definition of acid–base reactions, devised by Gilbert N.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Lewis in 1923, in the same year as Brønsted–Lowry, but it was not elaborated by him until 1938.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Instead of defining acid–base reactions in terms of protons or other bonded substances, the Lewis definition defines a base (referred to as a *Lewis base*) to be a compound that can donate an *electron pair*, and an acid (a *Lewis acid*) to be a compound that can receive this electron pair.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] For example, boron trifluoride, BF3 is a typical Lewis acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] It can accept a pair of electrons as it has a vacancy in its octet.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The fluoride ion has a full octet and can donate a pair of electrons.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Thus ${\ce {BF3 + F- -> BF4-}}$ is a typical Lewis acid, Lewis base reaction.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] All compounds of group 13 elements with a formula AX3 can behave as Lewis acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Similarly, compounds of group 15 elements with a formula DY3, such as amines, NR3, and phosphines, PR3, can behave as Lewis bases.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Adducts between them have the formula X3A←DY3 with a dative covalent bond, shown symbolically as ←, between the atoms A (acceptor) and D (donor).
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Compounds of group 16 with a formula DX2 may also act as Lewis bases; in this way, a compound like an ether, R2O, or a thioether, R2S, can act as a Lewis base.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The Lewis definition is not limited to these examples.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] For instance, carbon monoxide acts as a Lewis base when it forms an adduct with boron trifluoride, of formula F3B←CO.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Adducts involving metal ions are referred to as co-ordination compounds; each ligand donates a pair of electrons to the metal ion.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The reaction ${\ce {[Ag(H2O)4]+ + 2 NH3 -> [Ag(NH3)2]+ + 4 H2O}}$ can be seen as an acid–base reaction in which a stronger base (ammonia) replaces a weaker one (water).
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The Lewis and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are consistent with each other since the reaction ${\ce {H+ + OH- <=> H2O}}$ is an acid–base reaction in both theories.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] One of the limitations of the Arrhenius definition is its reliance on water solutions.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Edward Curtis Franklin studied the acid–base reactions in liquid ammonia in 1905 and pointed out the similarities to the water-based Arrhenius theory.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Germann, working with liquid phosgene, COCl 2, formulated the solvent-based theory in 1925, thereby generalizing the Arrhenius definition to cover aprotic solvents.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] A solute that causes an increase in the concentration of the solvonium ions and a decrease in the concentration of solvate ions is defined as an *acid*.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] A solute that causes an increase in the concentration of the solvate ions and a decrease in the concentration of the solvonium ions is defined as a *base*.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Thus, in liquid ammonia, KNH2 (supplying NH−2) is a strong base, and NH4NO3 (supplying NH+4) is a strong acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] In liquid sulfur dioxide (SO2), thionyl compounds (supplying SO2+) behave as acids, and sulfites (supplying SO2−3) behave as bases.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] On the other hand, solvent system theory has been criticized as being too general to be useful.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Also, it has been thought that there is something intrinsically acidic about hydrogen compounds, a property not shared by non-hydrogenic solvonium salts.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] This acid–base theory was a revival of the oxygen theory of acids and bases proposed by German chemist Hermann Lux in 1939, further improved by Håkon Flood c.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] 1947 and is still used in modern geochemistry and electrochemistry of molten salts.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] This definition describes an acid as an oxide ion (O2−) acceptor and a base as an oxide ion donor.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] This theory is also useful in the systematisation of the reactions of noble gas compounds, especially the xenon oxides, fluorides, and oxofluorides.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Mikhail Usanovich developed a general theory that does not restrict acidity to hydrogen-containing compounds, but his approach, published in 1938, was even more general than Lewis theory.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Usanovich's theory can be summarized as defining an acid as anything that accepts negative species or donates positive ones, and a base as the reverse.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] This defined the concept of redox (oxidation-reduction) as a special case of acid–base reactions.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] In 1963, Ralph Pearson proposed a qualitative concept known as the Hard and Soft Acids and Bases principle. later made quantitative with help of Robert Parr in 1984.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] 'Hard' applies to species that are small, have high charge states, and are weakly polarizable.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] 'Soft' applies to species that are large, have low charge states and are strongly polarizable.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Acids and bases interact, and the most stable interactions are hard–hard and soft–soft.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] This theory has found use in organic and inorganic chemistry.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Drago is a quantitative model that describes and predicts the strength of Lewis acid base interactions, −Δ*H*.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The model assigned E and C parameters to many Lewis acids and bases.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Each acid is characterized by an *E*A and a *C*A.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Each base is likewise characterized by its own *E*B and *C*B.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The E and C parameters refer, respectively, to the electrostatic and covalent contributions to the strength of the bonds that the acid and base will form.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The W term represents a constant energy contribution for acid–base reaction such as the cleavage of a dimeric acid or base.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The equation predicts reversal of acids and base strengths.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The graphical presentations of the equation show that there is no single order of Lewis base strengths or Lewis acid strengths.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The reaction of a strong acid with a strong base is essentially a quantitative reaction.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] In this reaction both the sodium and chloride ions are spectators as the neutralization reaction, ${\ce {H+ + OH- -> H2O}}$ does not involve them.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] With weak bases addition of acid is not quantitative because a solution of a weak base is a buffer solution.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] A solution of a weak acid is also a buffer solution.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] When a weak acid reacts with a weak base an equilibrium mixture is produced.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] The notation [X] signifies "concentration of X".
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] An acid–alkali reaction is a special case of an acid–base reaction, where the base used is also an alkali.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] When an acid reacts with an alkali salt (a metal hydroxide), the product is a metal salt and water.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Acid–alkali reactions are also neutralization reactions.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Acids are in general pure substances that contain hydrogen cations (H+) or cause them to be produced in solutions.
[src:hydrogen/acid-base-reaction] Hydrochloric acid (HCl) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4) are common examples.
[src:hydrogen/acid] An **acid** is a molecule or ion capable of either donating a proton (i.e. hydrogen cation, H+), known as a Brønsted–Lowry acid, or forming a covalent bond with an electron pair, known as a Lewis acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The first category of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion H3O+ and are known as Arrhenius acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents.
[src:hydrogen/acid] A Brønsted–Lowry or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable after loss of H+.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties that provide a practical description of an acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to form salts.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The word *acid* is derived from the Latin *acidus*, meaning 'sour'.
[src:hydrogen/acid] An aqueous solution of an acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as "acid" (as in "dissolved in acid"), while the strict definition refers only to the solute.
[src:hydrogen/acid] A lower pH means a higher **acidity**, and thus a higher concentration of hydrogen cations in the solution.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be **acidic**.
[src:hydrogen/acid] As these examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) that are solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which form a covalent bond with an electron pair.
[src:hydrogen/acid] An example is boron trifluoride (BF3), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital that can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH3).
[src:hydrogen/acid] Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly *or* by releasing protons (H+) into the solution, which then accept electron pairs.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted–Lowry acids cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair, however, and are therefore not Lewis acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In modern terminology, an *acid* is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as such.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Modern definitions are concerned with the fundamental chemical reactions common to all acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Most acids encountered in everyday life are aqueous solutions, or can be dissolved in water, so the Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are the most relevant.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The Brønsted–Lowry definition is the most widely used definition; unless otherwise specified, acid–base reactions are assumed to involve the transfer of a proton (H+) from an acid to a base.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Hydronium ions are acids according to all three definitions.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Although alcohols and amines can be Brønsted–Lowry acids, they can also function as Lewis bases due to the lone pairs of electrons on their oxygen and nitrogen atoms.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In 1884, Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen cations (H+), later described as protons or hydrons.
[src:hydrogen/acid] An **Arrhenius acid** is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H+ ions in the water.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Chemists often write H+(*aq*) and refer to the hydrogen cation when describing acid–base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the **hydronium ion** (H3O+) or other forms (H5O2+, H9O4+).
[src:hydrogen/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance that increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added to water.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Examples include molecular substances such as hydrogen chloride and acetic acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] An Arrhenius base, on the other hand, is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide (OH−) ions when dissolved in water.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Due to this equilibrium, any increase in the concentration of hydronium is accompanied by a decrease in the concentration of hydroxide.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid could also be said to be one that decreases hydroxide concentration, while an Arrhenius base increases it.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In an acidic solution, the concentration of hydronium ions is greater than 10−7 moles per liter.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Since pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of hydronium ions, acidic solutions thus have a pH of less than 7.
[src:hydrogen/acid] While the Arrhenius concept is useful for describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In 1923, chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid–base reactions involve the transfer of a proton.
[src:hydrogen/acid] A **Brønsted–Lowry acid** (or simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a proton to a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory has several advantages over Arrhenius theory.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Both theories easily describe the first reaction: CH3COOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because it acts as a source of H3O+ when dissolved in water, and it acts as a Brønsted acid by donating a proton to water.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In the second example CH3COOH undergoes the same transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH3), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does not produce hydronium.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Nevertheless, CH3COOH is both an Arrhenius and a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Brønsted–Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in nonaqueous solution or the gas phase.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Hydrogen chloride (HCl) and ammonia combine under several different conditions to form ammonium chloride, NH4Cl.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In aqueous solution HCl behaves as hydrochloric acid and exists as hydronium and chloride ions.
[src:hydrogen/acid] As with the acetic acid reactions, both definitions work for the first example, where water is the solvent and hydronium ion is formed by the HCl solute.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The next two reactions do not involve the formation of ions but are still proton-transfer reactions.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In the second reaction hydrogen chloride and ammonia (dissolved in benzene) react to form solid ammonium chloride in a benzene solvent and in the third gaseous HCl and NH3 combine to form the solid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Lewis, which includes reactions with acid–base characteristics that do not involve a proton transfer.
[src:hydrogen/acid] A **Lewis acid** is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; in other words, it is an electron pair acceptor.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Brønsted acid–base reactions are proton transfer reactions while Lewis acid–base reactions are electron pair transfers.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F−, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence electrons because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion.
[src:hydrogen/acid] BF3 is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride.
[src:hydrogen/acid] This reaction cannot be described in terms of Brønsted theory because there is no proton transfer.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The second reaction can be described using either theory.
[src:hydrogen/acid] A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, the oxygen atom in H3O+ gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Depending on the context, a Lewis acid may also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Organic Brønsted acids, such as acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] They dissociate in water to produce a Lewis acid, H+, but at the same time, they also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned).
[src:hydrogen/acid] This article deals mostly with Brønsted acids rather than Lewis acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Reactions of acids are often generalized in the form HA ⇌ H+ + A−, where HA represents the acid and A− is the conjugate base.
[src:hydrogen/acid] This reaction is referred to as **protolysis**.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The protonated form (HA) of an acid is also sometimes referred to as the **free acid**.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Acid–base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively).
[src:hydrogen/acid] The acid can be the charged species and the conjugate base can be neutral in which case the generalized reaction scheme could be written as HA+ ⇌ H+ + A.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and its conjugate base.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The equilibrium constant *K* is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Brackets indicate concentration, such that [H2O] means *the concentration of H2O*.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The acid dissociation constant *K*a is generally used in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The numerical value of *K*a is equal to the product (multiplication) of the concentrations of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H+.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The stronger of two acids will have a higher *K*a than the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen cations to acid will be higher for the stronger acid as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Because the range of possible values for *K*a spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable constant, p*K*a is more frequently used, where p*K*a = −log10 *K*a.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Stronger acids have a smaller p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Experimentally determined p*K*a at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Arrhenius acids are named according to their anions.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In the classical naming system, the ionic suffix is dropped and replaced with a new suffix, according to the table following.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The prefix "hydro-" is used when the acid is made up of just hydrogen and one other element.
[src:hydrogen/acid] For example, HCl has chloride as its anion, so the hydro- prefix is used, and the -ide suffix makes the name take the form hydrochloric acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In the IUPAC naming system, "aqueous" is simply added to the name of the ionic compound.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Thus, for hydrogen chloride, as an acid solution, the IUPAC name is aqueous hydrogen chloride.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The strength of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton.
[src:hydrogen/acid] A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of a strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H+ and one mole of the conjugate base, A−, and none of the protonated acid HA.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In contrast, a weak acid only partially dissociates and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic acid (HBr), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:hydrogen/acid] In water, each of these essentially ionizes 100%.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H+.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Acid strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Stronger acids have a larger acid dissociation constant, *K*a and a lower p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Sulfonic acids, which are organic oxyacids, are a class of strong acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] A common example is toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid).
[src:hydrogen/acid] Unlike sulfuric acid itself, sulfonic acids can be solids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In fact, polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is a solid strongly acidic plastic that is filterable.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Superacids are acids stronger than 100% sulfuric acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid, magic acid and perchloric acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The strongest known acid is helium hydride ion, with a proton affinity of 177.8kJ/mol.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Superacids can permanently protonate water to give ionic, crystalline hydronium "salts".
[src:hydrogen/acid] They can also quantitatively stabilize carbocations.
[src:hydrogen/acid] While *K*a measures the strength of an acid compound, the strength of an aqueous acid solution is measured by pH, which is an indication of the concentration of hydronium in the solution.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The pH of a simple solution of an acid compound in water is determined by the dilution of the compound and the compound's *K*a.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Lewis acids have been classified in the ECW model and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The relative acceptor strength of Lewis acids toward a series of bases, versus other Lewis acids, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:hydrogen/acid] It has been shown that to define the order of Lewis acid strength at least two properties must be considered.
[src:hydrogen/acid] For Pearson's qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for Drago's quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Common examples of monoprotic acids in mineral acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:hydrogen/acid] On the other hand, for organic acids the term mainly indicates the presence of one carboxylic acid group and sometimes these acids are known as monocarboxylic acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Examples in organic acids include formic acid (HCOOH), acetic acid (CH3COOH) and benzoic acid (C6H5COOH).
[src:hydrogen/acid] Polyprotic acids, also known as polybasic acids, are able to donate more than one proton per acid molecule, in contrast to monoprotic acids that only donate one proton per molecule.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Specific types of polyprotic acids have more specific names, such as diprotic (or dibasic) acid (two potential protons to donate), and triprotic (or tribasic) acid (three potential protons to donate).
[src:hydrogen/acid] Some macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids can have a very large number of acidic protons.
[src:hydrogen/acid] A diprotic acid (here symbolized by H2A) can undergo one or two dissociations depending on the pH.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Each dissociation has its own dissociation constant, Ka1 and Ka2.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The first dissociation constant is typically greater than the second (i.e., *K*a1 > *K*a2).
[src:hydrogen/acid] For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) can donate one proton to form the bisulfate anion (HSO− 4), for which *K*a1 is very large; then it can donate a second proton to form the sulfate anion (SO2− 4), wherein the *K*a2 is intermediate strength.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The large *K*a1 for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In a similar manner, the weak unstable carbonic acid (H2CO3) can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion (HCO− 3) and lose a second to form carbonate anion (CO2− 3).
[src:hydrogen/acid] Both *K*a values are small, but *K*a1 > *K*a2 .
[src:hydrogen/acid] A triprotic acid (H3A) can undergo one, two, or three dissociations and has three dissociation constants, where *K*a1 > *K*a2 > *K*a3.
[src:hydrogen/acid] An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (H3PO4), usually just called phosphoric acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] All three protons can be successively lost to yield H2PO− 4, then HPO2− 4, and finally PO3− 4, the orthophosphate ion, usually just called phosphate.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Even though the positions of the three protons on the original phosphoric acid molecule are equivalent, the successive *K*a values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged.
[src:hydrogen/acid] An organic example of a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the citrate ion.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Although the subsequent loss of each hydrogen ion is less favorable, all of the conjugate bases are present in solution.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The fractional concentration, *α* (alpha), for each species can be calculated.
[src:hydrogen/acid] For example, a generic diprotic acid will generate 3 species in solution: H2A, HA−, and A2−.
[src:hydrogen/acid] A plot of these fractional concentrations against pH, for given *K*1 and *K*2, is known as a Bjerrum plot.
[src:hydrogen/acid] where *K*0 = 1 and the other K-terms are the dissociation constants for the acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Neutralization is the basis of titration, where a pH indicator shows equivalence point when the equivalent number of moles of a base have been added to an acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] It is often wrongly assumed that neutralization should result in a solution with pH 7.0, which is only the case with similar acid and base strengths during a reaction.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Neutralization with a base weaker than the acid results in a weakly acidic salt.
[src:hydrogen/acid] An example is the weakly acidic ammonium chloride, which is produced from the strong acid hydrogen chloride and the weak base ammonia.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Conversely, neutralizing a weak acid with a strong base gives a weakly basic salt (e.g., sodium fluoride from hydrogen fluoride and sodium hydroxide).
[src:hydrogen/acid] In order for a protonated acid to lose a proton, the pH of the system must rise above the p*K*a of the acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The decreased concentration of H+ in that basic solution shifts the equilibrium towards the conjugate base form (the deprotonated form of the acid).
[src:hydrogen/acid] In lower-pH (more acidic) solutions, there is a high enough H+ concentration in the solution to cause the acid to remain in its protonated form.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Solutions of weak acids and salts of their conjugate bases form buffer solutions.
[src:hydrogen/acid] To determine the concentration of an acid in an aqueous solution, an acid–base titration is commonly performed.
[src:hydrogen/acid] A strong base solution with a known concentration, usually NaOH or KOH, is added to neutralize the acid solution according to the color change of the indicator with the amount of base added.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The titration curve of an acid titrated by a base has two axes, with the base volume on the x-axis and the solution's pH value on the y-axis.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The pH of the solution always goes up as the base is added to the solution.
[src:hydrogen/acid] For each diprotic acid titration curve, from left to right, there are two midpoints, two equivalence points, and two buffer regions.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Due to the successive dissociation processes, there are two equivalence points in the titration curve of a diprotic acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The first equivalence point occurs when all first protons from the first ionization are titrated.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In other words, the amount of OH− added equals the original amount of H2A at the first equivalence point.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The second equivalence point occurs when all protons are titrated.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Therefore, the amount of OH− added equals twice the amount of H2A at this time.
[src:hydrogen/acid] For a weak diprotic acid titrated by a strong base, the second equivalence point must occur at pH above 7 due to the hydrolysis of the resulted salts in the solution.
[src:hydrogen/acid] At either equivalence point, adding a drop of base will cause the steepest rise of the pH value in the system.
[src:hydrogen/acid] A titration curve for a diprotic acid contains two midpoints where pH=pKa.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Since there are two different Ka values, the first midpoint occurs at pH=pKa1 and the second one occurs at pH=pKa2.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Each segment of the curve that contains a midpoint at its center is called the buffer region.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Because the buffer regions consist of the acid and its conjugate base, it can resist pH changes when base is added until the next equivalent points.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Acids are fundamental reagents in treating almost all processes in modern industry.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Sulfuric acid, a diprotic acid, is the most widely used acid in industry, and is also the most-produced industrial chemical in the world.
[src:hydrogen/acid] It is mainly used in producing fertilizer, detergent, batteries and dyes, as well as used in processing many products such like removing impurities.
[src:hydrogen/acid] According to the statistics data in 2011, the annual production of sulfuric acid was around 200 million tonnes in the world.
[src:hydrogen/acid] For example, phosphate minerals react with sulfuric acid to produce phosphoric acid for the production of phosphate fertilizers, and zinc is produced by dissolving zinc oxide into sulfuric acid, purifying the solution and electrowinning.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In the chemical industry, acids react in neutralization reactions to produce salts.
[src:hydrogen/acid] For example, nitric acid reacts with ammonia to produce ammonium nitrate, a fertilizer.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Additionally, carboxylic acids can be esterified with alcohols, to produce esters.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Acids are often used to remove rust and other corrosion from metals in a process known as pickling.
[src:hydrogen/acid] They may be used as an electrolyte in a wet cell battery, such as sulfuric acid in a car battery.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Tartaric acid is an important component of some commonly used foods like unripe mangoes and tamarind.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Natural fruits and vegetables also contain acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Citric acid is present in oranges, lemon and other citrus fruits.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Oxalic acid is present in tomatoes, spinach, and especially in carambola and rhubarb; rhubarb leaves and unripe carambolas are toxic because of high concentrations of oxalic acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) is an essential vitamin for the human body and is present in such foods as amla (Indian gooseberry), lemon, citrus fruits, and guava.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Many acids can be found in various kinds of food as additives, as they alter their taste and serve as preservatives.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Phosphoric acid, for example, is a component of cola drinks.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Acetic acid is used in day-to-day life as vinegar.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Citric acid is used as a preservative in sauces and pickles.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Carbonic acid is one of the most common acid additives that are widely added in soft drinks.
[src:hydrogen/acid] During the manufacturing process, CO2 is usually pressurized to dissolve in these drinks to generate carbonic acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Carbonic acid is very unstable and tends to decompose into water and CO2 at room temperature and pressure.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Therefore, when bottles or cans of these kinds of soft drinks are opened, the soft drinks fizz and effervesce as CO2 bubbles come out.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) is used as a pain killer and for bringing down fevers.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Acids play important roles in the human body.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The hydrochloric acid present in the stomach aids digestion by breaking down large and complex food molecules.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Amino acids are required for synthesis of proteins required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Fatty acids are also required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Nucleic acids are important for the manufacturing of DNA and RNA and transmitting of traits to offspring through genes.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Carbonic acid is important for maintenance of pH equilibrium in the body.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Human bodies contain a variety of organic and inorganic compounds, among those dicarboxylic acids play an essential role in many biological behaviors.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Many of those acids are amino acids, which mainly serve as materials for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Other weak acids serve as buffers with their conjugate bases to keep the body's pH from undergoing large scale changes that would be harmful to cells.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The rest of the dicarboxylic acids also participate in the synthesis of various biologically important compounds in human bodies.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Acids are used as catalysts in industrial and organic chemistry; for example, sulfuric acid is used in very large quantities in the alkylation process to produce gasoline.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Some acids, such as sulfuric, phosphoric, and hydrochloric acids, also effect dehydration and condensation reactions.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In biochemistry, many enzymes employ acid catalysis.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Many biologically important molecules are acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Nucleic acids, which contain acidic phosphate groups, include DNA and RNA.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Nucleic acids contain the genetic code that determines many of an organism's characteristics, and is passed from parents to offspring.
[src:hydrogen/acid] DNA contains the chemical blueprint for the synthesis of proteins, which are made up of amino acid subunits.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Cell membranes contain fatty acid esters such as phospholipids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] An α-amino acid has a central carbon (the α or *alpha* carbon) that is covalently bonded to a carboxyl group (thus they are carboxylic acids), an amino group, a hydrogen atom and a variable group.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The variable group, also called the R group or side chain, determines the identity and many of the properties of a specific amino acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In glycine, the simplest amino acid, the R group is a hydrogen atom, but in all other amino acids it is contains one or more carbon atoms bonded to hydrogens, and may contain other elements such as sulfur, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:hydrogen/acid] With the exception of glycine, naturally occurring amino acids are chiral and almost invariably occur in the L-configuration.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Peptidoglycan, found in some bacterial cell walls contains some D-amino acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] At physiological pH, typically around 7, free amino acids exist in a charged form, where the acidic carboxyl group (-COOH) loses a proton (-COO−) and the basic amine group (-NH2) gains a proton (-NH+ 3).
[src:hydrogen/acid] The entire molecule has a net neutral charge and is a zwitterion, with the exception of amino acids with basic or acidic side chains.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Aspartic acid, for example, possesses one protonated amine and two deprotonated carboxyl groups, for a net charge of −1 at physiological pH.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Fatty acids and fatty acid derivatives are another group of carboxylic acids that play a significant role in biology.
[src:hydrogen/acid] These contain long hydrocarbon chains and a carboxylic acid group on one end.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The cell membrane of nearly all organisms is primarily made up of a phospholipid bilayer, a micelle of hydrophobic fatty acid esters with polar, hydrophilic phosphate "head" groups.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Membranes contain additional components, some of which can participate in acid–base reactions.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In humans and many other animals, hydrochloric acid is a part of the gastric acid secreted within the stomach to help hydrolyze proteins and polysaccharides, as well as converting the inactive pro-enzyme, pepsinogen into the enzyme, pepsin.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Some organisms produce acids for defense; for example, ants produce formic acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Acid–base equilibrium plays a critical role in regulating mammalian breathing.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Oxygen gas (O2) drives cellular respiration, the process by which animals release the chemical potential energy stored in food, producing carbon dioxide (CO2) as a byproduct.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged in the lungs, and the body responds to changing energy demands by adjusting the rate of ventilation.
[src:hydrogen/acid] For example, during periods of exertion the body rapidly breaks down stored carbohydrates and fat, releasing CO2 into the blood stream.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In aqueous solutions such as blood CO2 exists in equilibrium with carbonic acid and bicarbonate ion.
[src:hydrogen/acid] It is the decrease in pH that signals the brain to breathe faster and deeper, expelling the excess CO2 and resupplying the cells with O2.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Cell membranes are generally impermeable to charged or large, polar molecules because of the lipophilic fatty acyl chains comprising their interior.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Many biologically important molecules, including a number of pharmaceutical agents, are organic weak acids that can cross the membrane in their protonated, uncharged form but not in their charged form (i.e., as the conjugate base).
[src:hydrogen/acid] For this reason the activity of many drugs can be enhanced or inhibited by the use of antacids or acidic foods.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The charged form, however, is often more soluble in blood and cytosol, both aqueous environments.
[src:hydrogen/acid] When the extracellular environment is more acidic than the neutral pH within the cell, certain acids will exist in their neutral form and will be membrane soluble, allowing them to cross the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Acids that lose a proton at the intracellular pH will exist in their soluble, charged form and are thus able to diffuse through the cytosol to their target.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Ibuprofen, aspirin and penicillin are examples of drugs that are weak acids.
[src:hydrogen/acid] A sulfonic acid has the general formula RS(=O)2–OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:hydrogen/acid] A carboxylic acid has the general formula R-C(O)OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:hydrogen/acid] The carboxyl group -C(O)OH contains a carbonyl group, C=O, and a hydroxyl group, O-H.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Halogenation at alpha position increases acid strength, so that the following acids are all stronger than acetic acid.
[src:hydrogen/acid] Normal carboxylic acids are the direct union of a carbonyl group and a hydroxyl group.
[src:hydrogen/acid] In vinylogous carboxylic acids, a carbon-carbon double bond separates the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] A soft, silvery-white radioactive metal, actinium reacts rapidly with oxygen and moisture in air, forming a white coating of actinium oxide that prevents further oxidation.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] As with most lanthanides and many actinides, actinium assumes oxidation state +3 in nearly all its chemical compounds.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Actinium is found only in traces in uranium and thorium ores as the isotope 227Ac, which decays with a half-life of 21.772 years, predominantly emitting beta and sometimes alpha particles, and 228Ac, which is beta active with a half-life of 6.15 hours.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] One tonne of natural uranium in ore contains about 0.2 milligrams of actinium-227, and one tonne of thorium contains about 5 nanograms of actinium-228.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The close similarity of physical and chemical properties of actinium and lanthanum makes the separation of actinium from the ore impractical.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Instead, the element is prepared, in milligram amounts, by the neutron irradiation of 226Ra in a nuclear reactor.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Owing to its scarcity, high price, and radioactivity, actinium has no significant industrial use.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Its current applications include a neutron source and an agent for radiation therapy.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] André-Louis Debierne, a French chemist, announced the discovery of a new element in 1899.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] He separated it from pitchblende residues left by Marie and Pierre Curie after they had extracted radium.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] In 1899, Debierne described the substance as similar to titanium and (in 1900) as similar to thorium.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Friedrich Oskar Giesel found in 1902 a substance similar to lanthanum and called it "emanium" in 1904.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Articles published in the 1970s and later suggest that Debierne's results published in 1904 conflict with those reported in 1899 and 1900.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] This has led some authors to advocate that Giesel alone should be credited with the discovery.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] A less confrontational vision of scientific discovery is proposed by Adloff.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] He suggests that hindsight criticism of the early publications should be mitigated by the then nascent state of radiochemistry: highlighting the prudence of Debierne's claims in the original papers, he notes that nobody can contend that Debierne's substance did not contain actinium.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Debierne, who is now considered by the vast majority of historians as the discoverer, lost interest in the element and left the topic.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Giesel, on the other hand, can rightfully be credited with the first preparation of radiochemically pure actinium and with the identification of its atomic number 89.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The name actinium originates from the Ancient Greek *aktis, aktinos* (ακτίς, ακτίνος), meaning beam or ray.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Its symbol Ac is also used in abbreviations of other compounds that have nothing to do with actinium, such as acetyl, acetate and sometimes acetaldehyde.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Actinium is a soft, silvery-white, radioactive, metallic element.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Its estimated shear modulus is similar to that of lead.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Owing to its strong radioactivity, actinium glows in the dark with a pale blue light, which originates from the surrounding air ionized by the emitted energetic particles.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Actinium has similar chemical properties to lanthanum and other lanthanides, and therefore these elements are difficult to separate when extracting from uranium ores.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Solvent extraction and ion chromatography are commonly used for the separation.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The first element of the actinides, actinium, gave the set its name, much as lanthanum had done for the lanthanides.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The actinides are much more diverse than the lanthanides and therefore it was not until 1945 that the most significant change to Dmitri Mendeleev's periodic table since the recognition of the lanthanides, the introduction of the actinides, was generally accepted after Glenn T.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Seaborg's research on the transuranium elements (although it had been proposed as early as 1892 by British chemist Henry Bassett).
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Actinium reacts rapidly with oxygen and moisture in air, forming a white coating of actinium oxide that impedes further oxidation.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] As with most lanthanides and actinides, actinium exists in the oxidation state +3, and the Ac3+ ions are colorless in solutions.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The oxidation state +3 originates from the [Rn] 6d17s2 electronic configuration of actinium, with three valence electrons that are easily donated to give the stable closed-shell structure of the noble gas radon.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Although the 5f orbitals are unoccupied in an actinium atom, it can be used as a valence orbital in actinium complexes and hence it is generally considered the first 5f element by authors working on it.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Ac3+ is the largest of all known tripositive ions and its first coordination sphere contains approximately 10.9 ± 0.5 water molecules.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Due to actinium's intense radioactivity, only a limited number of actinium compounds are known.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] These include: AcF3, AcCl3, AcBr3, AcOF, AcOCl, AcOBr, Ac2S3, Ac2O3, AcPO4 and Ac(NO3)3.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] They all contain actinium in the oxidation state +3.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] In particular, the lattice constants of the analogous lanthanum and actinium compounds differ by only a few percent.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Here *a*, *b* and *c* are lattice constants, No is the space group number, and *Z* is the number of formula units per unit cell.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Density was not measured directly but calculated from the lattice parameters.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Actinium oxide (Ac2O3) can be obtained by heating the hydroxide at 500 °C (932 °F) or the oxalate at 1,100 °C (2,010 °F), in vacuum.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Its crystal lattice is isotypic with the oxides of most trivalent rare-earth metals.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Actinium trifluoride can be produced either in solution or in solid reaction.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The former reaction is carried out at room temperature, by adding hydrofluoric acid to a solution containing actinium ions.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] In the latter method, actinium metal is treated with hydrogen fluoride vapors at 700 °C (1,292 °F) in an all-platinum setup.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Treating actinium trifluoride with ammonium hydroxide at 900–1,000 °C (1,650–1,830 °F) yields oxyfluoride AcOF.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Whereas lanthanum oxyfluoride can be easily obtained by burning lanthanum trifluoride in air at 800 °C (1,470 °F) for an hour, similar treatment of actinium trifluoride yields no AcOF and only results in melting of the initial product.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Actinium trichloride is obtained by reacting actinium hydroxide or oxalate with carbon tetrachloride vapors at temperatures above 960 °C (1,760 °F).
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Similarly to the oxyfluoride, actinium oxychloride can be prepared by hydrolyzing actinium trichloride with ammonium hydroxide at 1,000 °C (1,830 °F).
[src:hydrogen/actinium] However, in contrast to the oxyfluoride, the oxychloride could well be synthesized by igniting a solution of actinium trichloride in hydrochloric acid with ammonia.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] and treating it with ammonium hydroxide at 500 °C (932 °F) results in the oxybromide AcOBr.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Actinium hydride was obtained by reduction of actinium trichloride with potassium at 300 °C (572 °F), and its structure was deduced by analogy with the corresponding LaH2 hydride.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The source of hydrogen in the reaction was uncertain.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Mixing monosodium phosphate (NaH2PO4) with a solution of actinium in hydrochloric acid yields white-colored actinium phosphate hemihydrate (AcPO4·0.5H2O), and heating actinium oxalate with hydrogen sulfide vapors at 1,400 °C (2,550 °F) for a few minutes results in a black actinium sulfide Ac2S3.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] It may be produced by acting with a mixture of hydrogen sulfide and carbon disulfide on actinium oxide at 1,000 °C (1,830 °F).
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Naturally occurring actinium is principally composed of two radioactive isotopes; 227Ac (from the radioactive family of 235U) and 228Ac (a granddaughter of 232Th).
[src:hydrogen/actinium] 227Ac decays mainly as a beta emitter with a very small energy, but in 1.38% of cases it emits an alpha particle, so it can readily be identified through alpha spectrometry.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Thirty-three radioisotopes have been identified, the most stable being 227Ac with a half-life of 21.772 years, 225Ac with a half-life of 10.0 days and 226Ac with a half-life of 29.37 hours.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] All remaining radioactive isotopes have half-lives that are less than 10 hours, and the majority of them have half-lives shorter than one minute.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The shortest-lived known isotope of actinium is 217Ac (half-life of 69 nanoseconds) which decays through alpha decay.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Actinium also has two known meta states.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The most significant isotopes for chemistry are 225Ac, 227Ac, and 228Ac.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Purified 227Ac comes into equilibrium with its decay products after about a half-year.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] It decays according to its 21.772-year half-life, emitting mostly beta (98.62%) and some alpha particles (1.38%); the successive decay products are part of the actinium series.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Owing to the low available amounts, low energy of its beta particles (maximum 44.8 keV) and low intensity of alpha radiation, 227Ac is difficult to detect directly by its emission, and it is therefore traced via its decay products.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The isotopes of actinium range in atomic weight from 203 Da (203Ac) to 236 Da (236Ac).
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Actinium is found only in traces in uranium ores – one tonne of uranium in ore contains about 0.2 milligrams of 227Ac – and in thorium ores, which contain about 5 nanograms of 228Ac per one tonne of thorium.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The actinium isotope 227Ac is a transient member of the uranium-actinium series decay chain, which begins with the parent isotope 235U (or 239Pu) and ends with the stable lead isotope 207Pb.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The isotope 228Ac is a transient member of the thorium series decay chain, which begins with the parent isotope 232Th and ends with the stable lead isotope 208Pb.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The low natural concentration and the close similarity of physical and chemical properties to those of lanthanum and other lanthanides, which are always abundant in actinium-bearing ores, render separation of actinium from the ore impractical.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The most concentrated actinium sample prepared from raw material consisted of 7 micrograms of 227Ac in less than 0.1 milligrams of La2O3, and complete separation was never achieved.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Instead, actinium is prepared, in milligram amounts, by the neutron irradiation of 226Ra in a nuclear reactor.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The reaction yield is about 2% of the radium weight.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] 227Ac can further capture neutrons resulting in small amounts of 228Ac.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] After the synthesis, actinium is separated from radium and from the products of decay and nuclear fusion, such as thorium, polonium, lead, and bismuth.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The extraction can be performed with thenoyltrifluoroacetone-benzene solution from an aqueous solution of the radiation products, and the selectivity to a certain element is achieved by adjusting the pH (to about 6.0 for actinium).
[src:hydrogen/actinium] An alternative procedure is anion exchange with an appropriate resin in nitric acid, which can result in a separation factor of 1,000,000 for radium and actinium vs. thorium in a two-stage process.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Actinium can then be separated from radium, with a ratio of about 100, using a low cross-linking cation exchange resin and nitric acid as eluant.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] 225Ac was first produced artificially at the Institute for Transuranium Elements (ITU) in Germany using a cyclotron and at St George Hospital in Sydney using a linac in 2000.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] This rare isotope has potential applications in radiation therapy and is most efficiently produced by bombarding a radium-226 target with 20–30 MeV deuterium ions.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] This reaction also yields 226Ac which however decays with a half-life of 29 hours and thus does not contaminate 225Ac.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Actinium metal has been prepared by the reduction of actinium fluoride with lithium vapor in vacuum at a temperature between 1,100 and 1,300 °C (2,010 and 2,370 °F).
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Higher temperatures resulted in evaporation of the product, and lower temperatures led to an incomplete transformation.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Lithium was chosen among other alkali metals because its fluoride is the most volatile.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Owing to its scarcity, high price and radioactivity, 227Ac currently has no significant industrial use, but 225Ac is currently being studied for use in cancer treatments such as targeted alpha therapies.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] 227Ac is highly radioactive and was therefore studied for use as an active element of radioisotope thermoelectric generators, for example, in spacecraft.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The oxide of 227Ac pressed with beryllium is also an efficient neutron source with the activity exceeding that of the standard americium-beryllium and radium-beryllium pairs.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] In all those applications, 227Ac (a beta source) is merely a progenitor which generates alpha-emitting isotopes upon its decay.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The 227AcBe neutron sources can be applied in a neutron probe – a standard device for measuring the quantity of water present in soil, as well as moisture/density for quality control in highway construction.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Such probes are also used in well logging applications, in neutron radiography, tomography, and other radiochemical investigations.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] 225Ac is applied in medicine to produce 213Bi in a reusable generator or can be used alone as an agent for radiation therapy, in particular targeted alpha therapy (TAT).
[src:hydrogen/actinium] This isotope has a half-life of 10 days, making it much more suitable for radiation therapy than 213Bi (half-life 46 minutes).
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Additionally, 225Ac decays to nontoxic 209Bi rather than toxic lead, which is the final product in the decay chains of several other candidate isotopes, namely 227Th, 228Th, and 230U.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Not only 225Ac itself, but also its daughters, emit alpha particles which kill cancer cells in the body.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The major difficulty with the application of 225Ac was that intravenous injection of simple actinium complexes resulted in their accumulation in the bones and liver for a period of tens of years.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] As a result, after the cancer cells were quickly killed by alpha particles from 225Ac, the radiation from the actinium and its daughters might induce new mutations.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] To solve this problem, 225Ac was bound to a chelating agent, such as citrate, ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid (EDTA) or diethylene triamine pentaacetic acid (DTPA).
[src:hydrogen/actinium] This reduced actinium accumulation in the bones, but the excretion from the body remained slow.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Much better results were obtained with such chelating agents as HEHA (1,4,7,10,13,16-hexaazacyclohexadecane-N,N′,N″,N‴,N‴′,N‴″-hexaacetic acid) or DOTA (1,4,7,10-tetraazacyclododecane-1,4,7,10-tetraacetic acid) coupled to trastuzumab, a monoclonal antibody that interferes with the HER2/neu receptor.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The latter delivery combination was tested on mice and proved to be effective against leukemia, lymphoma, breast, ovarian, neuroblastoma and prostate cancers.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The medium half-life of 227Ac (21.77 years) makes it a very convenient radioactive isotope in modeling the slow vertical mixing of oceanic waters.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The associated processes cannot be studied with the required accuracy by direct measurements of current velocities (of the order 50 meters per year).
[src:hydrogen/actinium] However, evaluation of the concentration depth profiles for different isotopes allows estimating the mixing rates.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] The physics behind this method is as follows: oceanic waters contain homogeneously dispersed 235U.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Its decay product, 231Pa, gradually precipitates to the bottom, so that its concentration first increases with depth and then stays nearly constant.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] 231Pa decays to 227Ac; however, the concentration of the latter isotope does not follow the 231Pa depth profile, but instead increases toward the sea bottom.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] This occurs because of the mixing processes, which raise some additional 227Ac from the sea bottom.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Thus, analysis of both 231Pa and 227Ac depth profiles allows researchers to model the mixing behavior.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] There are theoretical predictions that AcHx hydrides (in this case with very high pressure) are a candidate for a near room-temperature superconductor as they have Tc significantly higher than H3S, possibly near 250 K.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] 227Ac is highly radioactive and experiments with it are carried out in a specially designed laboratory equipped with a tight glove box.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] When actinium trichloride is administered intravenously to rats, about 33% of actinium is deposited into the bones and 50% into the liver.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] Its toxicity is comparable to, but slightly lower than, that of americium and plutonium.
[src:hydrogen/actinium] For trace quantities, fume hoods with good aeration suffice; for gram amounts, hot cells with shielding from the intense gamma radiation emitted by 227Ac are necessary.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Because it is so porous on a microscopic scale, activated carbon has a surface area of over 3,000 square metres per gram (920,000 square feet per ounce), as determined by gas absorption, and its porosity can run 10ML/day in terms of treated water per gram.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Researchers at Cornell University synthesized an ultrahigh surface area activated carbon with a BET area of 4,800 m2/g (1,500,000 sq ft/oz).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] This BET area value is the highest reported in the literature for activated carbon.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] For charcoal, the equivalent figure before activation is about 2–5 square metres per gram (610–1,530 sq ft/oz).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] A useful activation level may be obtained solely from the high surface area.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Further chemical treatment often enhances adsorption properties.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon is usually derived from waste products such as coconut husks in addition to other agricultural wastes like olive stones, rice husks and nutshells which are being upcycled into activated carbon, diversifying feedstock supply.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Waste from paper mills has been studied as a possible source of activated carbon.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] These bulk sources are converted into charcoal before being activated.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Using waste streams not only reduces landfill burden but also works to lower the overall carbon footprint as previously discarded waste is repurposed.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] When derived from coal, it is referred to as **activated coal**.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] **Activated coke** is derived from coke.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] These multiuse applications make it a versatile form of carbon that is used daily in many industries.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] There are many industrial applications of activated carbon and its other forms such as areas like metal extraction, water purification, sewage treatment, metal finishing and more.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] For example, it is the main purification technique for removing organic impurities from bright nickel plating solutions used for metal finishing plants.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Expanding on electroplating, a variety of organic chemicals can be added to the plating solutions for improving their deposit qualities and for enhancing properties like brightness, smoothness, ductility, etc.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] This is due to the passage of direct current and electrolytic reactions of anodic oxidation and cathodic reduction, organic additives generate unwanted breakdown products in solution.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Their excessive build up in the solutions can adversely affect plating quality and physical properties of deposited metal if run untreated by the filters.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon treatment removes such impurities and restores plating performance to the desired level.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Its installation costs may vary according to the volume of water it must process, however the average cost can be around USD 1 - 2 million.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Additionally, these filters need replacing over time (typically 6–12 months depending on usage).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The cost of replacing the carbon in the GAC filter form is about USD 0.05 - 0.1 per cubic meter of water that is treated in the plant.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon is used to treat poisonings and overdoses following oral ingestion.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Tablets or capsules of activated carbon are used in many countries as an over-the-counter drug to treat diarrhea, indigestion, and flatulence.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon will not prevent these chemicals from being absorbed into the human body.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] It is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Incorrect application (e.g. into the lungs) results in pulmonary aspiration, which can sometimes be fatal if immediate medical treatment is not initiated.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon, in 50% w/w combination with celite, is used as stationary phase in low-pressure chromatographic separation of carbohydrates (mono-, di-, tri-saccharides) using ethanol solutions (5–50%) as mobile phase in analytical or preparative protocols.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon is useful for extracting the direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs) such as dabigatran, apixaban, rivaroxaban and edoxaban from blood plasma samples.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] For this purpose it has been made into "minitablets", each containing 5 mg activated carbon for treating 1ml samples of DOAC.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Since this activated carbon has no effect on blood clotting factors, heparin or most other anticoagulants this allows a plasma sample to be analyzed for abnormalities otherwise affected by the DOACs.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] During early implementation of the 1974 Safe Drinking Water Act in the US, EPA officials developed a rule that proposed requiring drinking water treatment systems to use granular activated carbon.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Because of its high cost, the so-called GAC rule encountered strong opposition across the country from the water supply industry, including the largest water utilities in California.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon filtration is an effective water treatment method due to its multi-functional nature.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] There are specific types of activated carbon filtration methods and equipment that are indicated – depending upon the contaminants involved.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] In wastewater treatment, granulated activated carbon filters are implemented as an additional treatment step for removal of organic micropollutants such as pharmaceutical products, many of which are not entirely removed in traditional wastewater treatment processes.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Pollutants adsorb to the activated carbon granules and are then degraded by microorganisms on the filters.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon is also used for the measurement of radon concentration in air.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Biomass waste-derived activated carbons were also successfully used for the removal of caffeine and paracetamol from water.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon (charcoal) is an allowed substance used by organic farmers in both livestock production and wine making.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] In livestock production it is used as a pesticide, animal feed additive, processing aid, nonagricultural ingredient and disinfectant.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] In organic winemaking, activated carbon is allowed for use as a processing agent to adsorb brown color pigments from white grape concentrates.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon filters (AC filters) can be used to filter vodka and whiskey of organic impurities which can affect color, taste, and odor.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Passing an organically impure vodka through an activated carbon filter at the proper flow rate will result in vodka with an identical alcohol content and significantly increased organic purity, as judged by odor and taste.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Research is being done testing various activated carbons' ability to store natural gas and hydrogen gas.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The porous material acts like a sponge for different types of gases.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The gas is attracted to the carbon material via Van der Waals forces.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Some carbons have been able to achieve binding energies of 5–10 kJ per mol.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The gas may then be desorbed when subjected to higher temperatures and either combusted to do work or in the case of hydrogen gas extracted for use in a hydrogen fuel cell.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Gas storage in activated carbons is an appealing gas storage method because the gas can be stored in a low pressure, low mass, low volume environment that would be much more feasible than bulky on-board pressure tanks in vehicles.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The United States Department of Energy has specified certain goals to be achieved in the area of research and development of nano-porous carbon materials.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] All of the goals are yet to be satisfied but numerous institutions, including the ALL-CRAFT program, are continuing to conduct work in this field.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Filters with activated carbon are usually used in compressed air and gas purification to remove oil vapors, odor, and other hydrocarbons from the air.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The most common designs use a 1-stage or 2 stage filtration principle in which activated carbon is embedded inside the filter media.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon filters are used to retain radioactive gases within the air vacuumed from a nuclear boiling water reactor turbine condenser.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The large charcoal beds adsorb these gases and retain them while they rapidly decay to nonradioactive solid species.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The solids are trapped in the charcoal particles, while the filtered air passes through.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon is commonly used on the laboratory scale to purify solutions of organic molecules containing unwanted colored organic impurities.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Filtration over activated carbon is used in large scale fine chemical and pharmaceutical processes for the same purpose.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The carbon is either mixed with the solution then filtered off or immobilized in a filter.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon, often infused with sulfur or iodine, is widely used to trap mercury emissions from coal-fired power stations, medical incinerators, and from natural gas at the wellhead.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] However, despite its effectiveness, activated carbon is expensive to use.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Since it is often not recycled, the mercury-laden activated carbon presents a disposal dilemma.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] If the activated carbon contains less than 260 ppm mercury, United States federal regulations allow it to be stabilized (for example, trapped in concrete) for landfilling.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] However, waste containing greater than 260 ppm is considered to be in the high-mercury subcategory and is banned from landfilling (Land-Ban Rule).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] This material is now accumulating in warehouses and in deep abandoned mines at an estimated rate of 100 tons per year.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The problem of disposal of mercury-laden activated carbon is not unique to the United States.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] In the Netherlands, this mercury is largely recovered and the activated carbon is disposed of by complete burning, forming carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated, food-grade charcoal became a food trend in 2016, being used as an additive to impart a "slightly smoky" taste and a dark coloring to products including hotdogs, ice cream, pizza bases, and bagels.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] People taking medication, including birth control pills and antidepressants, are advised to avoid novelty foods or drinks that use activated charcoal coloring since it can render the medication ineffective.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated charcoal is used in smoking filters as a way to reduce the tar content and other chemicals present in smoke, which is a result of combustion, wherein it has been found to reduce the toxicants from tobacco smoke, in particular the free radicals.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The structure of activated carbon has long been a subject of debate.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] In a book published in 2006, Harry Marsh and Francisco Rodríguez-Reinoso considered more than 15 models for the structure, without coming to a definite conclusion about which was correct.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Recent work using aberration-corrected transmission electron microscopy has suggested that activated carbons may have a structure related to that of the fullerenes, with pentagonal and heptagonal carbon rings.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon is carbon produced from carbonaceous source materials such as bamboo, coconut husk, willow peat, wood, coir, lignite, coal, and petroleum pitch.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The source material is carbonized through pyrolysis at temperatures in the range 600–900 °C, usually in an inert atmosphere with gases such as argon or nitrogen.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] **Chemical activation**: Carbonaceous material is impregnated with certain chemicals.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The chemical is typically an acid, strong base, or a salt (phosphoric acid, potassium hydroxide, sodium hydroxide, potassium carbonate, sodium chloride, sodium carbonate, calcium chloride, and zinc chloride).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The carbon is then subjected to high temperatures (250–800 °C).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] It is believed that the temperature activates the carbon at this stage by forcing the material to open up and have more microscopic pores.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Chemical activation is preferred to physical activation owing to the lower temperatures, better quality consistency, and shorter time needed for activating the material.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The Dutch company Norit NV is one of the largest producer of activated carbon in the world.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Haycarb, a Sri Lankan coconut shell-based company, controls 16% of the global market share.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] After adsorption, spent granular activated carbon can often be regenerated rather than discarded.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Thermal reactivation (heating in an inert or steam atmosphere at 800–900 °C) restores much of the pore structure but consumes significant energy, while chemical regeneration (e.g. with dilute acids or bases) can selectively remove fouling compounds under milder conditions.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Emerging methods like microwave-assisted reactivation and bio-regeneration using fungi or bacteria show promise for lower-carbon footprints.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Choosing the optimal regeneration route balances carbon lifespan, energy use and treatment costs, and helps minimize the volume of hazardous waste sent to landfill.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbons are complex products which are difficult to classify on the basis of their behaviour, surface characteristics and other fundamental criteria.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] However, some broad classification is made for general purposes based on their size, preparation methods, and industrial applications.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Normally, activated carbons (R 1) are made in particulate form as powders or fine granules less than 1.0 mm in size with an average diameter between 0.15 and 0.25 mm.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Thus they present a large surface to volume ratio with a small diffusion distance.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon (R 1) is defined as the activated carbon particles retained on a 50-mesh sieve (0.297 mm).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Powdered activated carbon (PAC) material is finer material.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] PAC is made up of crushed or ground carbon particles, 95–100% of which will pass through a designated mesh sieve.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The ASTM classifies particles passing through an 80-mesh sieve (0.177 mm) and smaller as PAC.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] It is not common to use PAC in a dedicated vessel, due to the high head loss that would occur.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Instead, PAC is generally added directly to other process units, such as raw water intakes, rapid mix basins, clarifiers, and gravity filters.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Granular activated carbon (GAC) has a relatively larger particle size compared to powdered activated carbon and consequently, presents a smaller external surface.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Diffusion of the adsorbate is thus an important factor.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] These carbons are suitable for adsorption of gases, vapors and liquids, because these substances diffuse rapidly throughout the filters.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Granulated carbons are used for air filtration and water treatment, as well as for general deodorization and separation of components in flow systems and in rapid mix basins.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] GAC can be obtained in either granular or extruded form.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] GAC is designated by sizes such as 8×20, 20×40, or 8×30 for liquid phase applications and 4×6, 4×8 or 4×10 for vapor phase applications.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] A 20×40 carbon is made of particles that will pass through a U.S.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] 20 sieve (0.84 mm) (generally specified as 85% passing) but be retained on a U.S.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] 40 sieve (0.42 mm) (generally specified as 95% retained).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] AWWA (1992) B604 uses the 50-mesh sieve (0.297 mm) as the minimum GAC size.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The most popular aqueous-phase carbons are the 12×40 and 8×30 sizes because they have a good balance of size, surface area, and head loss characteristics.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Extruded activated carbon (EAC) combines powdered activated carbon with a binder, which are fused together and extruded into a cylindrical shaped activated carbon block with diameters from 0.8 to 130 mm.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] These are mainly used for gas phase applications because of their low pressure drop, high mechanical strength and low dust content.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Also sold as CTO filter (Chlorine, Taste, Odor).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Bead activated carbon (BAC) is manufactured from carbonizing petroleum pitch and then activating it into uniform spheres in diameters from approximately 0.35 to 0.80 mm.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] BAC typically exhibits a surface area in the range of 800–1 200 m2/g, comparable to or exceeding many granular carbons, enhancing its capacity for dissolved organics.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Similar to EAC, it is also noted for its low pressure drop, high mechanical strength and low dust content, but with a smaller grain size.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Its spherical shape makes it preferred for fluidized bed applications such as water filtration.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Porous carbons containing several types of inorganic impregnate such as iodine and silver.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Cations such as aluminium, manganese, zinc, iron, lithium, and calcium have also been prepared for specific application in air pollution control especially in museums and galleries.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Due to its antimicrobial and antiseptic properties, silver loaded activated carbon is used as an adsorbent for purification of domestic water.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Drinking water can be obtained from natural water by treating the natural water with a mixture of activated carbon and aluminium hydroxide (Al(OH)3), a flocculating agent.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Impregnated carbons are also used for the adsorption of hydrogen sulfide (H2S) and thiols.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Adsorption rates for H2S as high as 50% by weight have been reported.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] This is a process by which a porous carbon can be coated with a biocompatible polymer to give a smooth and permeable coat without blocking the pores.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The typical film thickness ranges from 50 to 200 nm, which strikes a balance between preserving pore access and ensuring mechanical stability in the material.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The resulting carbon is useful for hemoperfusion.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Hemoperfusion is a treatment technique in which large volumes of the patient's blood are passed over an adsorbent substance in order to remove toxic substances from the blood.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] In clinical trials, polymer-coated carbons have achieved over 80% removal of toxins such as bilirubin and certain drug metabolites in a single pass.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] There is a technology of processing technical rayon fiber into activated carbon cloth for carbon filtering.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Adsorption capacity of activated cloth is greater than that of activated charcoal (BET theory) surface area: 500–1500 m2/g, pore volume: 0.3–0.8 cm3/g).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Thanks to the different forms of activated material, it can be used in a wide range of applications (supercapacitors, odor absorbers, CBRN-defense industry etc.).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] A gram of activated carbon can have a surface area in excess of 500 m2 (5,400 sq ft), with 3,000 m2 (32,000 sq ft) being readily achievable.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Carbon aerogels, while more expensive, have even higher surface areas, and are used in special applications.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Under an electron microscope, the high surface-area structures of activated carbon are revealed.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Individual particles are intensely convoluted and display various kinds of porosity; there may be many areas where flat surfaces of graphite-like material run parallel to each other, separated by only a few nanometres or so.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] These micropores provide superb conditions for adsorption to occur, since adsorbing material can interact with many surfaces simultaneously.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] James Dewar, the scientist after whom the Dewar (vacuum flask) is named, spent much time in the early 20th century studying activated carbon, and published a paper regarding its adsorption capacity with regard to gases.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] In this paper, he discovered that cooling the carbon to liquid nitrogen temperatures allowed it to adsorb significant quantities of numerous air gases, among others, that could then be recollected by simply allowing the carbon to warm again and that coconut-based carbon was superior for the effect.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] He uses oxygen as an example, wherein the activated carbon would typically adsorb the atmospheric concentration (21%) under standard conditions, but release over 80% oxygen if the carbon was first cooled to low temperatures.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Physically, activated carbon binds materials by van der Waals force or London dispersion force.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon does not bind well to certain chemicals, including alcohols, diols, strong acids and bases, metals and most inorganics, such as lithium, sodium, iron, lead, arsenic, fluorine, and boric acid.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon can also adsorb iodine very well.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The iodine capacity, mg/g, (ASTM D28 Standard Method test) may be used as an indication of total adsorption over the surface area of the testing material.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Carbon monoxide however, is not very well adsorbed by activated carbon.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] This should be of particular concern to those using the material in filters for respirators, fume hoods, or other gas control systems because the gas is undetectable to the human senses, toxic to the metabolism, and neurotoxic which creates concern.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Substantial lists of the common industrial and agricultural gases adsorbed by activated carbon can be found online.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon can be used as a substrate for the application of various chemicals to improve the adsorptive capacity for some inorganic (and problematic organic) compounds such as hydrogen sulfide (H2S), ammonia (NH3), formaldehyde (HCOH), mercury (Hg) and radioactive iodine-131(131I).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] This property is known as chemisorption.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Many carbons preferentially adsorb small molecules.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Iodine number is the most fundamental parameter used to characterize activated carbon performance.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] It is a measure of activity level (higher number indicates higher degree of activation) often reported in mg/g (typical range 500–1200 mg/g).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] It is a measure of the micropore content of the activated carbon (0 to 20 Å, or up to 2 nm) by adsorption of iodine from solution.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] It is equivalent to surface area of carbon between 900 and 1100 m2/g.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] It is the standard measure for liquid-phase applications.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Iodine number is defined as the milligrams of iodine adsorbed by one gram of carbon when the iodine concentration in the residual filtrate is at a concentration of 0.02 normal (i.e.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Basically, iodine number is a measure of the iodine adsorbed in the pores and, as such, is an indication of the pore volume available in the activated carbon of interest.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Typically, water-treatment carbons have iodine numbers ranging from 600 to 1100.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Frequently, this parameter is used to determine the degree of exhaustion of a carbon in use.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] However, this practice should be viewed with caution, as chemical interactions with the adsorbate may affect the iodine uptake, giving false results.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Some carbons are more adept at adsorbing large molecules.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Molasses number or molasses efficiency is a measure of the mesopore content of the activated carbon (greater than 20 Å, or larger than 2 nm) by adsorption of molasses from solution.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] A high molasses number indicates a high adsorption of big molecules (range 95–600).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Caramel dp (decolorizing performance) is similar to molasses number.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Molasses efficiency is reported as a percentage (range 40%–185%) and parallels molasses number (600 = 185%, 425 = 85%).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The European molasses number (range 525–110) is inversely related to the North American molasses number.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Molasses Number is a measure of the degree of decolorization of a standard molasses solution that has been diluted and standardized against standardized activated carbon.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Due to the size of color bodies, the molasses number represents the potential pore volume available for larger adsorbing species.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] As all of the pore volume may not be available for adsorption in a particular waste water application, and as some of the adsorbate may enter smaller pores, it is not a good measure of the worth of a particular activated carbon for a specific application.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Frequently, this parameter is useful in evaluating a series of active carbons for their rates of adsorption.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Given two active carbons with similar pore volumes for adsorption, the one having the higher molasses number will usually have larger feeder pores resulting in more efficient transfer of adsorbate into the adsorption space.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Tannins are a mixture of large and medium size molecules.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Carbons with a combination of macropores and mesopores adsorb tannins.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The ability of a carbon to adsorb tannins is reported in parts per million concentration (range 200 ppm–362 ppm).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Some carbons have a mesopore (20 Å to 50 Å, or 2 to 5 nm) structure which adsorbs medium size molecules, such as the dye methylene blue.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Methylene blue adsorption is reported in g/100g (range 11–28 g/100g).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Some carbons are evaluated based on the dechlorination half-life length, which measures the chlorine-removal efficiency of activated carbon.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The dechlorination half-value length is the depth of carbon required to reduce the chlorine concentration by 50%.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] A lower half-value length indicates superior performance.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The solid or skeletal density of activated carbons will typically range between 2000 and 2100 kg/m3 (125–130 lbs./cubic foot).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] However, a large part of an activated carbon sample will consist of air space between particles, and the actual or apparent density will therefore be lower, typically 400 to 500 kg/m3 (25–31 lbs./cubic foot).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Higher density provides greater volume activity and normally indicates better-quality activated carbon.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] ASTM D 2854 -09 (2014) is used to determine the apparent density of activated carbon.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] It is a measure of the activated carbon's resistance to attrition.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] It is an important indicator of activated carbon to maintain its physical integrity and withstand frictional forces which would cause the material to be defective.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] There are large differences in the hardness of activated carbons, depending on the raw material and activity levels (porosity) it is created for.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Ash reduces the overall activity of activated carbon and reduces the efficiency of reactivation.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The amount is exclusively dependent on the base raw material used to produce the activated carbon (e.g., coconut, wood, coal, etc.).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The metal oxides (Fe2O3) can leach out of activated carbon resulting in discoloration.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Acid/water-soluble ash content is more significant than total ash content.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Soluble ash content can be very important for aquarists, as ferric oxide can promote algal growths.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] A carbon with a low soluble ash content should be used for marine, freshwater fish and reef tanks to avoid heavy metal poisoning and excess plant/algal growth.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] ASTM (D2866 Standard Method test) is used to determine the ash content of activated carbon.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Measurement of the porosity of an activated carbon by the adsorption of saturated carbon tetrachloride vapour.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The finer the particle size of an activated carbon, the better the access to the surface area and the faster the rate of adsorption kinetics.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] In vapour phase systems this needs to be considered against pressure drop, which will affect energy cost.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Careful consideration of particle size distribution can provide significant operating benefits.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] However, in the case of using activated carbon for adsorption of minerals such as gold, the particle size should be in the range of 3.35–1.4 millimetres (0.132–0.055 in).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon with particle size less than 1 mm would not be suitable for elution (the stripping of mineral from an activated carbon).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Researchers at Cornell University synthesized an ultrahigh surface area activated carbon with a BET area of 4800 m2 g–1 and a total pore volume of 2.7 cm3 g–1.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] This BET area value is the highest reported in the literature for activated carbon to date.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Acid-base, oxidation-reduction and specific adsorption characteristics are strongly dependent on the composition of the surface functional groups.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The surface of conventional activated carbon is reactive, capable of oxidation by atmospheric oxygen and oxygen plasma steam, and also carbon dioxide and ozone.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Oxidation in the liquid phase is caused by a wide range of reagents (HNO3, H2O2, KMnO4).
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Through the formation of a large number of basic and acidic groups on the surface of oxidized carbon to sorption and other properties can differ significantly from the unmodified forms.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon can be nitrogenated by natural products or polymers or processing of carbon with nitrogenating reagents.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Activated carbon can interact with chlorine, bromine and fluorine.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Surface of activated carbon, like other carbon materials can be fluoralkylated by treatment with (per)fluoropolyether peroxide in a liquid phase, or with wide range of fluoroorganic substances by CVD-method.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Such materials combine high hydrophobicity and chemical stability with electrical and thermal conductivity and can be used as electrode material for super capacitors.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Sulfonic acid functional groups can be attached to activated carbon to give "starbons" which can be used to selectively catalyse the esterification of fatty acids.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Formation of such activated carbons from halogenated precursors gives a more effective catalyst which is thought to be a result of remaining halogens improving stability.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] It is reported about synthesis of activated carbon with chemically grafted superacid sites –CF2SO3H.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Some of the chemical properties of activated carbon have been attributed to presence of the surface active carbon double bond.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The Polyani adsorption theory is a popular method for analyzing adsorption of various organic substances to their surface.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The most commonly encountered form of chemisorption in industry, occurs when a solid catalyst interacts with a gaseous feedstock, the reactant/s.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The adsorption of reactant/s to the catalyst surface creates a chemical bond, altering the electron density around the reactant molecule and allowing it to undergo reactions that would not normally be available to it.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The reactivation or the regeneration of activated carbons involves restoring the adsorptive capacity of saturated activated carbon by desorbing adsorbed contaminants on the activated carbon surface.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The most common regeneration technique employed in industrial processes is thermal reactivation.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The heat treatment stage utilises the exothermic nature of adsorption and results in desorption, partial cracking and polymerization of the adsorbed organics.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] The final step aims to remove charred organic residue formed in the porous structure in the previous stage and re-expose the porous carbon structure regenerating its original surface characteristics.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] After treatment the adsorption column can be reused.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Per adsorption-thermal regeneration cycle between 5–15 wt% of the carbon bed is burnt off resulting in a loss of adsorptive capacity.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Thermal regeneration is a high energy process due to the high required temperatures making it both an energetically and commercially expensive process.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Plants that rely on thermal regeneration of activated carbon have to be of a certain size before it is economically viable to have regeneration facilities onsite.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] As a result, it is common for smaller waste treatment sites to ship their activated carbon cores to specialised facilities for regeneration.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Current concerns with the high energy/cost nature of thermal regeneration of activated carbon has encouraged research into alternative regeneration methods to reduce the environmental impact of such processes.
[src:hydrogen/activated-carbon] Though several of the regeneration techniques cited have remained areas of purely academic research, some alternatives to thermal regeneration systems have been employed in industry.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen gas was first produced artificially in the 17th century by the reaction of acids with metals.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Henry Cavendish, in 1766–1781, identified hydrogen gas as a distinct substance and discovered its property of producing water when burned: this is the origin of hydrogen's name, which means 'water-former' (from Ancient Greek: ὕδωρ, romanized: *húdōr*, lit.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] 'water', and γεννάω, *gennáō*, 'I bring forth').
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Understanding the colors of light absorbed and emitted by hydrogen was a crucial part of the development of quantum mechanics.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen, typically nonmetallic except under extreme pressure, readily forms covalent bonds with most nonmetals, contributing to the formation of compounds like water and various organic substances.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Its role is crucial in acid–base reactions, which mainly involve proton exchange among soluble molecules.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In ionic compounds, hydrogen can take the form of either a negatively-charged anion, where it is known as hydride, or as a positively charged cation, H+, hydron.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Although tightly bonded to water molecules, hydrons strongly affect the behavior of aqueous solutions, as reflected in the importance of pH.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydride, on the other hand, is rarely observed because it tends to deprotonate solvents, yielding H2.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In the early universe, neutral hydrogen atoms formed about 370,000 years after the Big Bang as the universe expanded and plasma had cooled enough for electrons to remain bound to protons.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] After stars began to form, most of the hydrogen in the intergalactic medium was re-ionized.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Nearly all hydrogen production is done by transforming fossil fuels, particularly steam reforming of natural gas.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] It can also be produced from water or saline by electrolysis, but this process is more expensive.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Its main industrial uses include fossil fuel processing and ammonia production for fertilizer.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Emerging uses for hydrogen include the use of fuel cells to generate electricity.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The ground state energy level of the electron in a hydrogen atom is −13.6 electronvolts (eV), equivalent to an ultraviolet photon of roughly 91 nanometers wavelength.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The energy levels of hydrogen are referred to by consecutive quantum numbers, with $n=1$ being the ground state.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The hydrogen spectral series corresponds to emission of light due to transitions from higher to lower energy levels.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Each energy level is further split by spin interactions between the electron and proton into four hyperfine levels.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] High-precision values for the hydrogen atom energy levels are required for definitions of physical constants.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Quantum calculations have identified nine contributions to the energy levels.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The eigenvalue from the Dirac equation is the largest contribution.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Other terms include relativistic recoil, the self-energy, and the vacuum polarization terms.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The standards organization for chemical names, IUPAC, gives general names when the context assumes natural isotope abundance or ignores the isotope.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] These general names are *hydrogen* for the neutral atom, *hydron* for the cation, H+, *hydride* for the anion, and H-.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The name *proton* is often used for the positively charged cation, but this is strictly correct only for the cation of the dominant isotope 1 H.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen has three naturally-occurring isotopes, denoted 1 H, 2 H and 3 H.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Other, highly-unstable nuclides (4 H to 7 H) have been synthesized in laboratories but not observed in nature.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Unique among the elements, distinct names are assigned to hydrogen's isotopes in common use.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] During the early study of radioactivity, heavy radioisotopes were given their own names, but these are mostly no longer used.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The symbols D and T (instead of 2 H and 3 H) are sometimes used for deuterium and tritium, but the symbol P was already used for phosphorus and thus was not available for protium.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In its nomenclatural guidelines, the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) allows any of D, T, 2 H, and 3 H to be used, though 2 H and 3 H are preferred.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Antihydrogen (H) is the antimatter counterpart to hydrogen.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] It consists of an anti­proton with a positron.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The exotic atom muonium (symbol Mu), composed of an antimuon and an electron, is the anti­matter analogue of hydrogen; IUPAC nomenclature incorporates such hypothetical compounds as muonium chloride (MuCl) and sodium muonide (NaMu), analogous to hydrogen chloride and sodium hydride respectively.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Under standard conditions, hydrogen is a gas of diatomic molecules with the formula H2, officially called "dihydrogen", but also called "molecular hydrogen", or simply hydrogen.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Dihydrogen is a colorless, odorless, flammable gas.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The amount of heat released per mole of hydrogen is −286 kilojoules (kJ), or 141.9 megajoules (MJ) for a one-kilogram (2.2 lb) mass (based on the higher heating value measurement).
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen gas forms explosive mixtures with air in concentrations from 4%–74% and with chlorine at 5%–95%.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The hydrogen autoignition temperature, the temperature of spontaneous ignition in air, is 500 °C (932 °F).
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In a high-pressure hydrogen leak, the shock wave from the leak itself can heat air to the autoignition temperature, leading to flaming and possibly explosion.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen flames emit faint blue and ultraviolet light.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Flame detectors are used to detect hydrogen fires as they are nearly invisible to the naked eye in daylight.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Molecular H2 exists as two nuclear isomers that differ in the spin states of their nuclei.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In the **ortho­hydrogen** form, the spins of the two nuclei are parallel, forming a spin triplet state having a total molecular spin $S=1$ ; in the **para­hydrogen** form the spins are anti­parallel and form a spin singlet state having spin $S=0$ .
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The equilibrium ratio of ortho- to para-hydrogen depends on temperature.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] At room temperature or warmer, equilibrium hydrogen gas contains about 25% of the para form and 75% of the ortho form.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The ortho form is an excited state, having higher energy than the para form by 1.455 kJ/mol, and it converts to the para form over the course of several minutes when cooled to low temperature.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The thermal properties of these isomers differ because each has distinct rotational quantum states.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The ortho-to-para ratio in H2 is an important consideration in the liquefaction and storage of liquid hydrogen: the conversion from ortho to para is exothermic, and produces sufficient heat to evaporate most of the liquid if the conversion to para­hydrogen does not occur during the cooling process.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Catalysts for the ortho-para inter­conversion, such as ferric oxide and activated carbon compounds, are therefore used during hydrogen cooling to avoid this loss of liquid.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Liquid hydrogen can exist at temperatures below hydrogen's critical point of 33 kelvins (−240.2 °C; −400.3 °F).
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] However, for it to be in a fully liquid state at atmospheric pressure, H2 needs to be cooled to 20.28 K (−252.87 °C; −423.17 °F).
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen was liquefied by James Dewar in 1898 by using regenerative cooling and his invention, the vacuum flask.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Liquid hydrogen becomes solid hydrogen at standard pressure below hydrogen's melting point of 14.01 K (−259.14 °C; −434.45 °F).
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Distinct solid phases exist, known as Phase I through Phase V, each exhibiting a characteristic molecular arrangement.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Liquid and solid phases can exist in combination at the triple point; this mixture is known as slush hydrogen.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Metallic hydrogen, a phase obtained at extremely high pressures (in excess of 400 billion Pa (58,000,000 psi)), is an electrical conductor.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] It is believed to exist deep within giant planets like Jupiter.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] When ionized, hydrogen becomes a plasma.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] This is the form in which hydrogen exists within stars.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In 1671, Irish scientist Robert Boyle discovered and described the reaction between iron filings and dilute acids, which results in the production of hydrogen gas.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Boyle did not note that the gas was flammable, but hydrogen would play a key role in overturning the phlogiston theory of combustion.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In 1766, Henry Cavendish was the first to recognize hydrogen gas as a discrete substance, by naming the gas from a metal-acid reaction "inflammable air".
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] He speculated that "inflammable air" was in fact identical to the hypothetical substance "phlogiston" and further finding in 1781 that the gas produces water when burned.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] He is usually given credit for the discovery of hydrogen as an element.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In 1783, Antoine Lavoisier identified the element that came to be known as hydrogen when he and Laplace reproduced Cavendish's finding that water is produced when hydrogen is burned.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Lavoisier produced hydrogen for his experiments on mass conservation by treating metallic iron with a stream of water through an incandescent iron tube heated in a fire.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Many metals react similarly with water, leading to the production of hydrogen.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In some situations, this H2-producing process is problematic, for instance in the case of zirconium cladding on nuclear fuel rods.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] By 1806 hydrogen was used to fill balloons.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] François Isaac de Rivaz built the first de Rivaz engine, an internal combustion engine powered by a mixture of hydrogen and oxygen, in 1806.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Edward Daniel Clarke invented the hydrogen gas blowpipe in 1819.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The Döbereiner's lamp and limelight were invented in 1823.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen was liquefied for the first time by James Dewar in 1898 by using regenerative cooling and his invention, the vacuum flask.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] He produced solid hydrogen the next year.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] According to quantum theory, this behavior arises from the spacing of the (quantized) rotational energy levels, which are particularly wide-spaced in H2 because of its low mass.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] These widely-spaced levels inhibit equal partition of heat energy into rotational motion in hydrogen at low temperatures.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Diatomic gases composed of heavier atoms do not have such widely spaced levels and do not exhibit the same effect.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The existence of the hydride anion was suggested by Gilbert N.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Lewis in 1916 for group 1 and group 2 salt-like compounds.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In 1920, Moers electrolyzed molten lithium hydride (LiH), producing a stoichiometric quantity of hydrogen at the anode.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Because of its simple atomic structure, consisting only of a proton and an electron, the hydrogen atom, together with the spectrum of light produced from it or absorbed by it, has been central to the development of the theory of atomic structure.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The energy levels of hydrogen can be calculated fairly accurately using the Bohr model of the atom, in which the electron "orbits" the proton, just as Earth orbits the Sun.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] However, the electron and proton are held together by electrostatic attraction, while planets and celestial objects are held by gravity.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Due to the discretization of angular momentum postulated in early quantum mechanics by Bohr, the electron in the Bohr model can only occupy certain allowed distances from the proton, and therefore only certain allowed energies.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen's unique position as the only neutral atom for which the Schrödinger equation can be directly solved has significantly contributed to the understanding of quantum mechanics through the exploration of its energetics.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Furthermore, study of the corresponding simplicity of the hydrogen molecule and the corresponding cation, H+2, brought understanding of the nature of the chemical bond, which followed shortly after the quantum mechanical treatment of the hydrogen atom had been developed in the mid-1920s.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Because H2 has only 7% the density of air, it was once widely used as a lifting gas in balloons and airships.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The first hydrogen-filled balloon was invented by Jacques Charles in 1783.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen provided the lift for the first reliable form of air-travel following the 1852 invention of the first hydrogen-lifted airship by Henri Giffard.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] German count Ferdinand von Zeppelin promoted the idea of rigid airships lifted by hydrogen that later were called Zeppelins, the first of which had its maiden flight in 1900.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Regularly-scheduled flights started in 1910 and by the outbreak of World War I in August 1914, they had carried 35,000 passengers without a serious incident.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen-lifted airships in the form of blimps were used as observation platforms and bombers during World War II, especially on the US Eastern seaboard.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The first non-stop transatlantic crossing was made by the British airship *R34* in 1919 and regular passenger service resumed in the 1920s.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen was used in the *Hindenburg*, which caught fire over New Jersey on 6 May 1937.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The hydrogen that filled the airship was ignited, possibly by static electricity, and burst into flames.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Following this disaster, commercial hydrogen airship travel ceased.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen is still used, in preference to non-flammable but more expensive helium, as a lifting gas for weather balloons.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Deuterium was discovered in December 1931 by Harold Urey, and tritium was prepared in 1934 by Ernest Rutherford, Mark Oliphant, and Paul Harteck.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Heavy water, which consists of deuterium in the place of regular hydrogen, was discovered by Urey's group in 1932.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The thermodynamic basis of this low reactivity is the very strong H–H bond, with a bond dissociation energy of 435.7 kJ/mol.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] It does form coordination complexes called dihydrogen complexes.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] These species provide insights into the early steps in the interactions of hydrogen with metal catalysts.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] According to neutron diffraction, the metal and two H atoms form a triangle in these complexes.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The H-H bond remains intact but is elongated.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Although exotic on Earth, the H+3 ion is common in the universe.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] It is a triangular species, like the aforementioned dihydrogen complexes.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] It is known as protonated molecular hydrogen or the trihydrogen cation.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen reacts with chlorine to produce HCl, and with bromine to produce HBr, via a chain reaction.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] For example, in the case of Br2, the dibromine molecule is split apart: Br2 + (UV light) → 2Br•.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The addition of H2 to unsaturated organic compounds, such as alkenes and alkynes, is called hydrogenation.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Even if the reaction is energetically favorable, it does not occur spontaneously even at higher temperatures.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In the presence of a catalyst like finely divided platinum or nickel, the reaction proceeds at room temperature.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen can exist in both +1 and −1 oxidation states, forming compounds through ionic and covalent bonding.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The element is part of a wide range of substances, including water, hydrocarbons, and numerous other organic compounds.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The H+ ion—commonly referred to as a proton due to its single proton and absence of electrons—is central to acid–base chemistry, although the proton does not move freely.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In the Brønsted–Lowry framework, acids are defined by their ability to donate H+ ions to bases.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen forms a vast variety of compounds with carbon, known as hydrocarbons, and an even greater diversity with other elements (heteroatoms), giving rise to the broad class of organic compounds often associated with living organisms.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen compounds with hydrogen in the oxidation state −1 are known as hydrides, which are usually formed between hydrogen and metals.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The hydrides can be ionic (aka saline), covalent, or metallic.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] With heating, H2 reacts efficiently with the alkali and alkaline earth metals to give the ionic hydrides of the formulas MH and MH2, respectively.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] These salt-like crystalline compounds have high melting points and all react with water to liberate hydrogen.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Covalent hydrides include boranes and polymeric aluminium hydride.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Transition metals form metal hydrides via continuous dissolution of hydrogen into the metal.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] A well-known hydride is lithium aluminium hydride: the [AlH4]− anion carries hydridic centers firmly attached to the Al(III).
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Perhaps the most extensive series of hydrides are the boranes, compounds consisting only of boron and hydrogen.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrides can bond to these electropositive elements not only as a terminal ligand but also as bridging ligands.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In diborane (B2H6), four hydrogen atoms are terminal, while two bridge between the two boron atoms.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] When bonded to a more electronegative element, particularly fluorine, oxygen, or nitrogen, hydrogen can participate in a form of medium-strength noncovalent bonding with another electronegative element with a lone pair like oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] This phenomenon, called hydrogen bonding, is critical to the stability of many biological molecules.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen bonding alters molecule structures, viscosity, solubility, melting and boiling points, and even protein folding dynamics.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In water, hydrogen bonding plays an important role in reaction thermodynamics.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] A hydrogen bond can shift over to proton transfer.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Under the Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory, acids are proton donors, while bases are proton acceptors.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] A bare proton (H+) essentially cannot exist in anything other than a vacuum.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Otherwise it attaches to other atoms, ions, or molecules.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Even chemical species as inert as methane can be protonated.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The term "proton" is used loosely and metaphorically to refer to solvated hydrogen cations attached to other chemical species; it is denoted "H+" without any implication that any single protons exist freely in solution as a species.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] To avoid the implication of the naked proton in solution, acidic aqueous solutions are sometimes considered to contain the "hydronium ion" ([H3O]+), or still more accurately, [H9O4]+.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Other oxonium ions are found when water is in acidic solution with other solvents.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The concentration of these solvated protons determines the pH of a solution, a logarithmic scale that reflects its acidity or basicity.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Lower pH values indicate higher concentrations of hydronium ions, corresponding to more acidic conditions.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen, as atomic H, is the most abundant chemical element in the universe, making up 75% of normal matter by mass. and >90% by number of atoms.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In the early universe, protons formed in the first second after the Big Bang; neutral hydrogen atoms formed about 370,000 years later during the recombination epoch as the universe expanded and plasma had cooled enough for electrons to remain bound to protons.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In astrophysics, neutral hydrogen in the interstellar medium is called *H I* and ionized hydrogen is called *H II*.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Radiation from stars ionizes H I to H II, creating spheres of ionized H II around stars.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In the chronology of the universe neutral hydrogen dominated until the birth of stars during the era of reionization, which then produced bubbles of ionized hydrogen that grew and merged over hundreds of millions of years.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] These are the source of the 21-centimeter hydrogen line, at 1420 MHz, that is detected in order to probe primordial hydrogen.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The large amount of neutral hydrogen found in the damped Lyman-alpha systems is thought to dominate the cosmological baryonic density of the universe up to a redshift of *z* = 4.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen is found in great abundance in stars and gas giant planets.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Molecular clouds of H2 are associated with star formation.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen plays a vital role in powering stars through the proton-proton reaction in lower-mass stars, and through the CNO cycle of nuclear fusion in stars more massive than the Sun.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Protonated molecular hydrogen (H+3) is found in the interstellar medium, where it is generated by ionization of molecular hydrogen by cosmic rays.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] This ion has also been observed in the upper atmosphere of Jupiter.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The ion is long-lived in outer space due to the low temperature and density.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] H+3 is one of the most abundant ions in the universe, and it plays a notable role in the chemistry of the interstellar medium.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Neutral triatomic hydrogen H3 can exist only in an excited form and is unstable.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen is the third most abundant element on the Earth's surface, mostly existing within chemical compounds such as hydrocarbons and water.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Elemental hydrogen is normally in the form of a gas, H2, at standard conditions.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] It is present in a very low concentration in Earth's atmosphere (around 0.53 parts per million on a molar basis) because of its light weight, which enables it to escape the atmosphere more rapidly than heavier gases.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Despite its low concentration in the atmosphere, terrestrial hydrogen is sufficiently abundant to support the metabolism of several varieties of bacteria.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Large underground deposits of hydrogen gas have been discovered in several countries including Mali, France and Australia.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] As of 2024, it is uncertain how much underground hydrogen can be extracted economically.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Nearly all of the world's current supply of hydrogen gas (H2) is produced from fossil fuels, with less than 1% of hydrogen being produced by low-emissions technologies in 2025.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Many methods exist for producing H2, but three dominate commercially: steam reforming often coupled to water-gas shift, partial oxidation of hydrocarbons, and water electrolysis.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen is mainly produced by steam methane reforming (SMR), the reaction of water and methane.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Producing one tonne of hydrogen through this process emits 6.6–9.3 tonnes of carbon dioxide.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The production of natural gas feedstock also produces emissions such as vented and fugitive methane, which further contributes to the overall carbon footprint of hydrogen.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] This reaction is favored at low pressures but is nonetheless conducted at high pressures (2.0 MPa [20 atm; 590 inHg]) because high-pressure H2 is the most marketable product, and pressure swing adsorption (PSA) purification systems work better at higher pressures.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The product mixture is known as "synthesis gas" because it is often used directly for the production of methanol and many other compounds.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrocarbons other than methane can be used to produce synthesis gas with varying product ratios.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Therefore, steam reforming typically employs an excess of H2O.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Additional hydrogen can be recovered from the steam by using carbon monoxide through the water gas shift reaction (WGS).
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen is sometimes produced and consumed in the same industrial process, without being separated.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In the Haber process for ammonia production, hydrogen is generated from natural gas.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Olefin production units may produce substantial quantities of byproduct hydrogen, particularly from cracking light feedstocks like ethane or propane.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Electrolysis of water is a conceptually simple method of producing hydrogen.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Commercial electrolyzers use nickel-based catalysts in strongly alkaline solution.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Platinum is a better catalyst but is expensive.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The hydrogen created through electrolysis using renewable energy is commonly referred to as "green hydrogen".
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Electrolysis of brine to yield chlorine also produces high-purity hydrogen as a co-product, which is used for a variety of transformations such as hydrogenations.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The electrolysis process is more expensive than producing hydrogen from methane without carbon capture and storage.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Innovation in hydrogen electrolyzers could make large-scale production of hydrogen from electricity more cost-competitive.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The carbon may be sold as a manufacturing feedstock or fuel, or landfilled.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] This route could have a lower carbon footprint than existing hydrogen production processes, but mechanisms for removing the carbon and preventing it from reacting with the catalyst remain obstacles for industrial-scale use.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Water splitting is the process by which water is decomposed into its components.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The reaction occurs in the light-dependent reactions in all photosynthetic organisms.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] A few organisms, including the alga *Chlamydomonas reinhardtii* and cyanobacteria, have evolved a second step in the dark reactions in which protons and electrons are reduced to form H2 gas by specialized hydrogenases in the chloroplast.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Efforts have been undertaken to genetically modify cyanobacterial hydrogenases to more efficiently generate H2 gas even in the presence of oxygen.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Efforts have also been undertaken with genetically‐modified alga in a bioreactor.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Over 200 thermochemical cycles can be used for water splitting.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] A number of labs (including in France, Germany, Greece, Japan, and the United States) are developing thermochemical methods to produce hydrogen from solar energy and water.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] H2 is produced in organisms by enzymes called hydrogenases.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] This process allows the host organism to use fermentation as a source of energy.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] These same enzymes also can oxidize H2, such that the host organisms can subsist by reducing oxidized substrates using electrons extracted from H2.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogenase enzymes feature iron or iron–nickel centers at their active sites.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The natural cycle of hydrogen production and consumption by organisms is called the hydrogen cycle.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Some bacteria such as *Mycobacterium smegmatis* can use the small amount of hydrogen in the atmosphere as a source of energy when other sources are lacking.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Their hydrogenases feature small channels that exclude oxygen from the active site, permitting the reaction to occur even though the hydrogen concentration is very low and the oxygen concentration is as in normal air.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Confirming the existence of hydrogenase‐employing microbes in the human gut, H2 occurs in human breath.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The concentration in the breath of fasting people at rest is typically under 5 parts per million (ppm), but can reach 50 ppm when people with intestinal disorders consume molecules they cannot absorb during diagnostic hydrogen breath tests.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Serpentinization is a geological mechanism which produces highly-reducing conditions.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] This process also is relevant to the corrosion of iron and steel in oxygen-free groundwater and in reducing soils below the water table.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen is also often a by-product of other reactions.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Many metals react with water to produce H2, but the rate of hydrogen evolution depends on the metal, the pH, and the presence of alloying agents.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Most often, hydrogen evolution is induced by acids.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The alkali and alkaline earth metals as well as aluminium, zinc, manganese, and iron, react readily with aqueous acids.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Many metals, such as aluminium, are slow to react with water because they form passivated oxide coatings.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] An alloy of aluminium and gallium, however, does react with water.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] If H2 is to be used as an energy source, its storage is important.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] For example, at room temperature and 0.1 millipascals (9.9×10−10 atm), approx.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] 0.05 moles of hydrogen dissolve into one kilogram (2.2 lb) of diethyl ether.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] H2 can be stored in compressed form, although compressing costs energy.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Liquefaction is impractical given hydrogen's low critical temperature.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In contrast, ammonia and many hydrocarbons can be liquified at room temperature under pressure.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] For these reasons, hydrogen *carriers*—materials that reversibly bind H2—have attracted much attention.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The key question is then the weight percent of H2-equivalents within the carrier material.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] For example, hydrogen can be reversibly absorbed into many rare earths and transition metals and is soluble in both nanocrystalline and amorphous metals.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen solubility in metals is influenced by local distortions or impurities in the crystal lattice.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] These properties may be useful when hydrogen is purified by passage through hot palladium disks, but the gas's high solubility is also a metallurgical problem, contributing to the embrittlement of many metals, complicating the design of pipelines and storage tanks.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The most problematic aspect of metal hydrides for storage is their modest H2 content, often on the order of 1%.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] For this reason, there is interest in storage of H2 in compounds of low molecular weight.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] For example, ammonia borane (H3N−BH3) contains 19.8 weight percent of H2.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The problem with this material is that after release of H2, the resulting boron nitride does not re-add H2: i.e., ammonia borane is an irreversible hydrogen carrier.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Large quantities of H2 are used in the "upgrading" of fossil fuels.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Key consumers of H2 include hydrodesulfurization and hydrocracking.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Many of these reactions can be classified as hydrogenolysis, i.e., the cleavage of bonds by hydrogen.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogenation, the addition of H2 to various substrates, is done on a large scale.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] This process consumes a few percent of the energy budget in the entire industry and is the biggest consumer of hydrogen.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The resulting ammonia is used extensively in fertilizer production; these fertilizers have become essential feedstocks in modern agriculture.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogenation is also used to convert unsaturated fats and oils to saturated fats and oils.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The major application is the production of margarine.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Methanol is produced by hydrogenation of carbon dioxide; the mixture of hydrogen and carbon dioxide used for this process is known as syngas.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] It is similarly the source of hydrogen in the manufacture of hydrochloric acid.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] H2 is also used as a reducing agent for the conversion of some ores to the metals.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The potential for using hydrogen (H2) as a fuel has been widely discussed.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen can be used in fuel cells to produce electricity, or burned to generate heat.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] When hydrogen is consumed in fuel cells, the only emission at the point of use is water vapor.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] When burned, hydrogen produces relatively little pollution at the point of combustion, but can lead to thermal formation of harmful nitrogen oxides.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] If hydrogen is produced with low or zero greenhouse gas emissions (green hydrogen), it can play a significant role in decarbonizing energy systems where there are challenges and limitations to replacing fossil fuels with direct use of electricity.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen fuel can produce the intense heat required for industrial production of steel, cement, glass, and chemicals, thus contributing to the decarbonization of industry alongside other technologies, such as electric arc furnaces for steelmaking.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] However, it is likely to play a larger role in providing industrial feedstock for cleaner production of ammonia and organic chemicals.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen used to decarbonize transportation is likely to find its largest applications in shipping, aviation and, to a lesser extent, heavy goods vehicles, through the use of hydrogen-derived synthetic fuels such as ammonia and methanol and fuel cell technology.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] For light-duty vehicles including cars, hydrogen is far behind other alternative fuel vehicles, especially compared with the rate of adoption of battery electric vehicles, and may not play a significant role in future.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen together serve as cryogenic propellants in liquid-propellant rockets, as in the Space Shuttle main engines.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] NASA has investigated the use of rocket propellant made from atomic hydrogen, boron or carbon that is frozen into solid molecular hydrogen particles suspended in liquid helium.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Upon warming, the mixture vaporizes to allow the atomic species to recombine, heating the mixture to high temperature.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen produced when there is a surplus of variable renewable electricity could in principle be stored and later used to generate heat or to re-generate electricity.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] It can be further transformed into synthetic fuels such as ammonia and methanol.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Disadvantages of hydrogen fuel include high costs of storage and distribution due to hydrogen's explosivity, its large volume compared to other fuels, and its tendency to embrittle materials.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The economic disadvantage of distribution can be reduced by co-locating facilities that use hydrogen in mining industry hubs.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The very long-lived, rechargeable nickel–hydrogen battery developed for satellite power systems uses pressurized gaseous H2.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The International Space Station, Mars Odyssey and the Mars Global Surveyor are equipped with nickel-hydrogen batteries.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In the dark part of its orbit, the Hubble Space Telescope is also powered by nickel-hydrogen batteries, which were finally replaced in May 2009, more than 19 years after launch and 13 years beyond their design life.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen is employed in semiconductor manufacturing to saturate broken ("dangling") bonds of amorphous silicon and amorphous carbon, which helps in stabilizing the materials' properties.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen, introduced as an unintended side-effect of production, acts as a shallow electron donor leading to n-type conductivity in ZnO, with important uses in transducers and phosphors.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Detailed analysis of ZnO and of MgO shows evidence of four and six-fold hydrogen multicentre bonds.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] The doping behavior of hydrogen varies with material.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In hydrogen pipelines and steel storage vessels, hydrogen molecules are prone to reacting with metals, causing hydrogen embrittlement and leaks in the pipeline or storage vessel.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Since it is lighter than air, hydrogen does not easily accumulate to form a combustible gas mixture.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] However, even without ignition sources, high-pressure hydrogen leakage may cause spontaneous combustion and detonation.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen is flammable when mixed even in small amounts with air.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Ignition can occur at a volumetric ratio of hydrogen to air as low as 4%.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] In approximately 70% of hydrogen ignition accidents, the ignition source cannot be determined.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen fire, while being extremely hot, is almost invisible to the human eye, and thus can lead to accidental burns.
[src:hydrogen/hydrogen] Hydrogen is non-toxic, but like most gases it can cause asphyxiation in the absence of adequate ventilation.
